# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The primary function of a User ID is to uniquely identify a user within a system.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Ideally, User IDs should be randomly generated to prevent the creation of predictable or sequential IDs, which could pose a security risk, especially in systems where User IDs might be exposed or inferred from external sources.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Usernames are easy-to-remember identifiers chosen by the user and used for identifying themselves when logging into a system or service.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The terms User ID and username might be used interchangeably if the username chosen by the user also serves as their unique identifier within the system.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Users should be permitted to use their email address as a username, provided the email is verified during sign-up.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Additionally, they should have the option to choose a username other than an email address.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For information on validating email addresses, please visit the input validation cheat sheet email discussion.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] A key concern when using passwords for authentication is password strength.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] A "strong" password policy makes it difficult or even improbable for one to guess the password through either manual or automated means.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It is common for an application to have a mechanism that provides a means for a user to gain access to their account in the event they forget their password.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Please see Forgot Password Cheat Sheet for details on this feature.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It is critical for an application to store a password using the right cryptographic technique.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Please see Password Storage Cheat Sheet for details on this feature.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Where possible, the user-supplied password should be compared to the stored password hash using a secure password comparison function provided by the language or framework, such as the password_verify() function in PHP.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The login page and all subsequent authenticated pages must be exclusively accessed over TLS or other strong transport.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Failure to utilize TLS or other strong transport for the login page allows an attacker to modify the login form action, causing the user's credentials to be posted to an arbitrary location.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Failure to utilize TLS or other strong transport for authenticated pages after login enables an attacker to view the unencrypted session ID and compromise the user's authenticated session.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] In order to mitigate CSRF and session hijacking, it's important to require the current credentials for an account before updating sensitive account information such as the user's password or email address -- or before sensitive transactions, such as shipping a purchase to a new address.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Without this countermeasure, an attacker may be able to execute sensitive transactions through a CSRF or XSS attack without needing to know the user's current credentials.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Additionally, an attacker may get temporary physical access to a user's browser or steal their session ID to take over the user's session.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Some applications should use a second factor to check whether a user may perform sensitive operations.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Transaction Authorization Cheat Sheet.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] TLS Client Authentication, also known as two-way TLS authentication, consists of both browser and server sending their respective TLS certificates during the TLS handshake process.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Just as you can validate the authenticity of a server by using the certificate and asking a verifiably-valid Certificate Authority (CA) if the certificate is valid, the server can authenticate the user by receiving a certificate from the client and validating against a third-party CA or its own CA.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] To do this, the server must provide the user with a certificate generated specifically for him, assigning values to the subject so that these can be used to determine what user the certificate should validate.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The user installs the certificate on a browser and now uses it for the website.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It is generally not a good idea to use this method for widely and publicly available websites that will have an average user.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For example, it wouldn't be a good idea to implement this for a website like Facebook.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] While this technique can prevent the user from having to type a password (thus protecting against an average keylogger from stealing it), it is still considered a good idea to consider using both a password and TLS client authentication combined.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Additionally, if the client is behind an enterprise proxy that performs SSL/TLS decryption, this will break certificate authentication unless the site is allowed on the proxy.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Incorrectly implemented error messages in the case of authentication functionality can be used for the purposes of user ID and password enumeration.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] An application should respond (both HTTP and HTML) in a generic manner.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The account registration feature should also be taken into consideration, and the same approach of a generic error message can be applied regarding the case in which the user exists.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The objective is to prevent the creation of a discrepancy factor, allowing an attacker to mount a user enumeration action against the application.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It is interesting to note that the business logic itself can bring a discrepancy factor related to the processing time taken.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Indeed, depending on the implementation, the processing time can be significantly different according to the case (success vs failure) allowing an attacker to mount a time-based attack (delta of some seconds for example).
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It can be clearly seen that if the user doesn't exist, the application will directly throw an error.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, when the user exists and the password doesn't, it is apparent that there will be more processing before the application errors out.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] In return, the response time will be different for the same error, allowing the attacker to differentiate between a wrong username and a wrong password.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] This code will go through the same process no matter what the user or the password is, allowing the application to return in approximately the same response time.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The problem with returning a generic error message for the user is a User Experience (UX) matter.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] A legitimate user might feel confused with the generic messages, thus making it hard for them to use the application, and might after several retries, leave the application because of its complexity.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The decision to return a *generic error message* can be determined based on the criticality of the application and its data.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For example, for critical applications, the team can decide that under the failure scenario, a user will always be redirected to the support page and a *generic error message* will be returned.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Regarding the user enumeration itself, protection against brute-force attacks is also effective because it prevents an attacker from applying the enumeration at scale.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Usage of CAPTCHA can be applied to a feature for which a *generic error message* cannot be returned because the *user experience* must be preserved.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The application may return a different HTTP Error code depending on the authentication attempt response.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It may respond with a 200 for a positive result and a 403 for a negative result.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Even though a generic error page is shown to a user, the HTTP response code may differ which can leak information about whether the account is valid or not.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Error disclosure can also be used as a discrepancy factor, consult the error handling cheat sheet regarding the global handling of different errors in an application.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] There are a number of different types of automated attacks that attackers can use to try and compromise user accounts.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Different protection mechanisms can be implemented to protect against these attacks.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] In many cases, these defenses do not provide complete protection, but when a number of them are implemented in a defense-in-depth approach, a reasonable level of protection can be achieved.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The following sections will focus primarily on preventing brute-force attacks, although these controls can also be effective against other types of attacks.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For further guidance on defending against credential stuffing and password spraying, see the Credential Stuffing Cheat Sheet.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Multi-factor authentication (MFA) is by far the best defense against the majority of password-related attacks, including brute-force attacks, with analysis by Microsoft suggesting that it would have stopped 99.9% of account compromises.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] As such, it should be implemented wherever possible; however, depending on the audience of the application, it may not be practical or feasible to enforce the use of MFA.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The Multifactor Authentication Cheat Sheet contains further guidance on implementing MFA.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The most common protection against these attacks is to implement account lockout, which prevents any more login attempts for a period after a certain number of failed logins.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The counter of failed logins should be associated with the account itself, rather than the source IP address, in order to prevent an attacker from making login attempts from a large number of different IP addresses.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Rather than implementing a fixed lockout duration (e.g., ten minutes), some applications use an exponential lockout, where the lockout duration starts as a very short period (e.g., one second), but doubles after each failed login attempt.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] When designing an account lockout system, care must be taken to prevent it from being used to cause a denial of service by locking out other users' accounts.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] One way this could be performed is to allow the use of the forgotten password functionality to log in, even if the account is locked out.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The use of an effective CAPTCHA can help to prevent automated login attempts against accounts.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] However, many CAPTCHA implementations have weaknesses that allow them to be solved using automated techniques or can be outsourced to services that can solve them.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] As such, the use of CAPTCHA should be viewed as a defense-in-depth control to make brute-force attacks more time-consuming and expensive, rather than as a preventative.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It may be more user-friendly to only require a CAPTCHA be solved after a small number of failed login attempts, rather than requiring it from the very first login.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The addition of a security question or memorable word can also help protect against automated attacks, especially when the user is asked to enter a number of randomly chosen characters from the word.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It should be noted that this does **not** constitute multi-factor authentication, as both factors are the same (something you know).
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Furthermore, security questions are often weak and have predictable answers, so they must be carefully chosen.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The Choosing and Using Security Questions cheat sheet contains further guidance on this.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] While authentication through a combination of username, password, and multi-factor authentication is considered generally secure, there are use cases where it isn't considered the best option or even safe.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Examples of this are third-party applications that desire to connect to the web application, either from a mobile device, another website, desktop, or other situations.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] When this happens, it is NOT considered safe to allow the third-party application to store the user/password combo, since then it extends the attack surface into their hands, where it isn't in your control.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For this and other use cases, there are several authentication protocols that can protect you from exposing your users' data to attackers.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] OAuth is an **authorization** framework for delegated access to APIs.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is often considered to compete with OpenId.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The most recommended version is 2.0 since it is very feature-complete and provides strong security.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Like OpenId, SAML uses identity providers, but unlike OpenId, it is XML-based and provides more flexibility.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] SAML is based on browser redirects which send XML data.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Furthermore, SAML isn't only initiated by a service provider; it can also be initiated from the identity provider.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] This allows the user to navigate through different portals while still being authenticated without having to do anything, making the process transparent.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It is more common to see SAML being used inside of intranet websites, sometimes even using a server from the intranet as the identity provider.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The Fast Identity Online (FIDO) Alliance has created two protocols to facilitate online authentication: the Universal Authentication Framework (UAF) protocol and the Universal Second Factor (U2F) protocol.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] While UAF focuses on passwordless authentication, U2F allows the addition of a second factor to existing password-based authentication.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Both protocols are based on a public key cryptography challenge-response model.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] UAF takes advantage of existing security technologies present on devices for authentication including fingerprint sensors, cameras (face biometrics), microphones (voice biometrics), Trusted Execution Environments (TEEs), Secure Elements (SEs), and others.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The protocol is designed to plug these device capabilities into a common authentication framework.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] UAF works with both native applications and web applications.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] U2F augments password-based authentication using a hardware token (typically USB) that stores cryptographic authentication keys and uses them for signing.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] The user can use the same token as a second factor for multiple applications.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] It provides **protection against phishing** by using the URL of the website to look up the stored authentication key.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For many authenticators, including common platform passkeys, the private key is generated and stored by the operating system's secure key manager.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Depending on the platform and authenticator, keys may be protected using hardware-backed components such as the Trusted Platform Module (TPM) on Windows, Secure Enclave on Apple devices, or the Android Keystore/StrongBox on Android, or by other software-based mechanisms.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] In typical implementations, the private key is intended to be non-exportable and bound to the authenticator, and the platform security module signs a server challenge using this key.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] However, some authenticators support credential synchronization or backup that may involve export or server-side storage, and not all implementations are hardware-backed.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Relying parties should not assume that keys are hardware-backed and non-exportable unless this is verified (for example, via authenticator properties or attestation).
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Password managers are programs, browser plugins, or web services that automate the management of a large quantity of different credentials.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Most password managers have functionality to allow users to easily use them on websites, either: (a) by pasting the passwords into the login form -- or -- (b) by simulating the user typing them in.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Describe the process for changing the registered email address to the user.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Ask the user to submit a proposed new email address, ensuring it complies with system rules.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Request the use of Multifactor Authentication for identity verification.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Store the proposed new email address as a pending change.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Create and store **two** time-limited nonces for (a) system administrators' notification, and (b) user confirmation.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Handle responses from the links accordingly.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Request the user's current password for identity verification.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Create and store three time-limited nonces for system administrators' notification, user confirmation, and an additional step for password reliance.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] For example, an application may require MFA for the first login from a particular device but not for subsequent logins from that device.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] Alternatively, a single sign-on solution may authenticate the user and allow them to remain logged in for a day but require a reauthentication if they try to access their profile page.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] An example might be to allow someone to trigger something to see their current bank balance, but not the account number or anything else.
[src:security/authentication-cheat-sheet] If they need to see transactions, then the application puts them through some base level authentication and if they want to do any money movement, then MFA is required.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attack occurs when a malicious web site, email, blog, instant message, or program tricks an authenticated user's web browser into performing an unwanted action on a trusted site.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If a target user is authenticated to the site, unprotected target sites cannot distinguish between legitimate authorized requests and forged authenticated requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Since browser requests automatically include all cookies including session cookies, this attack works unless proper authorization is used, which means that the target site's challenge-response mechanism does not verify the identity and authority of the requester.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In effect, CSRF attacks make a target system perform attacker-specified functions via the victim's browser without the victim's knowledge (normally until after the unauthorized actions have been committed).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] However, successful CSRF attacks can only exploit the capabilities exposed by the vulnerable application and the user's privileges.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on the user's credentials, the attacker can transfer funds, change a password, make an unauthorized purchase, elevate privileges for a target account, or take any action that the user is permitted to do.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Before building a custom token or Fetch-Metadata implementation, check whether your framework or platform already provides CSRF protection you can use.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Built-in defenses are generally preferable because they’re maintained by the framework authors and reduce the risk of subtle implementation mistakes.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The synchronizer token pattern is one of the most popular and recommended methods to mitigate CSRF.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] CSRF tokens should be generated on the server-side and they should be generated only once per user session or each request.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Because the time range for an attacker to exploit the stolen tokens is minimal for per-request tokens, they are more secure than per-session tokens.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] However, using per-request tokens may result in usability concerns.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, the "Back" button browser capability can be hindered by a per-request token as the previous page may contain a token that is no longer valid.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In this case, interaction with a previous page will result in a CSRF false positive security event on the server-side.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If per-session token implementations occur after the initial generation of a token, the value is stored in the session and is used for each subsequent request until the session expires.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] When a client issues a request, the server-side component must verify the existence and validity of the token in that request and compare it to the token found in the user session.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The request should be rejected if that token was not found within the request or the value provided does not match the value within the user session.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Additional actions such as logging the event as a potential CSRF attack in progress should also be considered.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] CSRF tokens prevent CSRF because without a CSRF token, an attacker cannot create valid requests to the backend server.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The CSRF token can be transmitted to the client as part of a response payload, such as a HTML or JSON response, then it can be transmitted back to the server as a hidden field on a form submission or via an AJAX request as a custom header value or part of a JSON payload.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A CSRF token should not be transmitted in a cookie for synchronized patterns.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A CSRF token must not be leaked in the server logs or in the URL.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] GET requests can potentially leak CSRF tokens at several locations, such as the browser history, log files, network utilities that log the first line of a HTTP request, and Referer headers if the protected site links to an external site.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Since requests with custom headers are automatically subject to the same-origin policy, it is more secure to insert the CSRF token in a custom HTTP request header via JavaScript than adding a CSRF token in the hidden field form parameter.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If maintaining the state for CSRF token on the server is problematic, you can use an alternative technique known as the Double Submit Cookie pattern.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This technique is easy to implement and is stateless.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] There are different ways to implement this technique, where the *naive* pattern is the most commonly used variation.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The most secure implementation of the Double Submit Cookie pattern is the *Signed Double-Submit Cookie*, which explicitly ties tokens to the user's authenticated session (e.g., session ID).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Simply signing tokens without session binding provides minimal protection and remains vulnerable to cookie injection attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Always bind the CSRF token explicitly to session-specific data.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the token contains sensitive information (like session IDs or claims), always use Hash-based Message Authentication (HMAC) with a server-side secret key.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This prevents token forgery while ensuring integrity.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] HMAC is preferred over simple hashing in all cases as it protects against various cryptographic attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For scenarios requiring confidentiality of token contents, use authenticated encryption instead.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] It's a common misconception to include timestamps as a value to specify the CSRF token expiration time.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] They are used to verify the authenticity of requests throughout a session, using session information.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A new session should generate a new token (1).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Note: The `constantTimeEquals` function should be used to compare the HMACs to prevent timing attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This function compares two strings in constant time, regardless of how many characters match.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The *Naive Double-Submit Cookie* method is a scalable and easy-to-implement technique which uses a cryptographically strong random value as a cookie and as a request parameter (even before user authentication).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Then the server verifies if the cookie value and request value match.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The site must require that every transaction request from the user includes this random value as a **custom request header or form parameter ONLY.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the value matches at server side, the server accepts it as a legitimate request and if they don't, it rejects the request.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Since an attacker is unable to access the cookie value during a cross-site request, they cannot include a matching value in the hidden form value or as a request parameter/header.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Though the Naive Double-Submit Cookie method is simple and scalable, it remains vulnerable to cookie injection attacks, especially when attackers control subdomains or network environments allowing them to plant or overwrite cookies.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance, an attacker-controlled subdomain (e.g., via DNS takeover) could inject a matching cookie and thus forge a valid request token.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This resource details these vulnerabilities.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, always prefer the *Signed Double-Submit Cookie* pattern with session-bound HMAC tokens to mitigate these threats.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Fetch Metadata request headers provide extra information about the context from which an HTTP request was made.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Servers can use these headers — most importantly `Sec-Fetch-Site` — as a lightweight and reliable method to block obvious cross-site requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Fetch Metadata specification for details.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Because some legacy browsers do not send `Sec-Fetch-*` headers, a fallback to standard origin verification headers **is a mandatory requirement** for any Fetch Metadata implementation.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] `Sec-Fetch-*` is supported in all major browsers since March 2023.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If any of the headers above contain values not listed in the specification, in order to support forward-compatibility, servers should ignore those headers.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Unlike synchronizer tokens or double-submit patterns — which require additional client/server coordination and are difficult to implement correctly — Fetch Metadata checks are much more straightforward.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] They typically require only a small amount of server-side logic (inspect Sec-Fetch-Site, optionally refine with Sec-Fetch-Mode/Sec-Fetch-Dest) and no client changes.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] That simplicity reduces complexity, making the approach attractive for many applications.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Fetch Metadata request headers are supported in all modern browsers on both desktop and mobile (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Safari 16.4+, and even in webviews on both iOS and Android), with over 98% global coverage.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For compatibility detail, see the browser support table.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For the rare cases of outdated or embedded browsers that lack `Sec-Fetch-*` support, a fallback to standard origin verification should provide the required coverage.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If this is acceptable for your project, consider prompting users to update their browsers, as they are running on outdated and potentially insecure versions.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] `Sec-Fetch-Site` is the most useful Fetch Metadata header for blocking CSRF-like cross-origin requests and should be the primary signal in a Fetch-Metadata-based policy.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Use other Fetch Metadata headers (`Sec-Fetch-Mode`, `Sec-Fetch-Dest`, `Sec-Fetch-User`) to further refine or tailor policies to your application's needs (for example, allowing top-level navigation requests or permitting specific Dest values for resource endpoints).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] 3.1 To ensure that your site can still be linked from other sites, you have to allow simple (HTTP GET) top-level navigation.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] 3.2 Whitelist explicit cross-origin flows.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If certain endpoints intentionally accept cross-origin requests (CORS JSON APIs, third-party integrations, webhooks), explicitly exempt those endpoints from the global Sec-Fetch deny policy and secure them with proper CORS configuration, authentication, and logging.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] When a `<form>` tag is used to submit data, it sends a "simple" request that browsers do not designate as "to be preflighted".
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] These "simple" requests introduce risk of CSRF because browsers permit them to be sent to any origin.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If your application uses `<form>` tags to submit data anywhere in your client, you will still need to protect them with alternate approaches described in this document such as tokens.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For a request to be deemed simple, it must have one of the following content types - `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, `multipart/form-data` or `text/plain`.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Many modern web applications use JSON APIs so would naturally require CORS, however they may accept `text/plain` which would be vulnerable to CSRF.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore a simple mitigation is for the server or API to disallow these simple content types.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Both the synchronizer token and the double-submit cookie are used to prevent forgery of form data, but they can be tricky to implement and degrade usability.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Many modern web applications do not use `<form>` tags to submit data.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A user-friendly defense that is particularly well suited for AJAX or API endpoints is the use of a **custom request header**.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In this pattern, the client appends a custom header to requests that require CSRF protection.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The header can be any arbitrary key-value pair, as long as it does not conflict with existing headers.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] While any arbitrary header name will work, using one of these standard names can improve compatibility with existing tools and developer expectations.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] When handling the request, the API checks for the existence of this header.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the header does not exist, the backend rejects the request as potential forgery.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This defense relies on the CORS preflight mechanism which sends an `OPTIONS` request to verify CORS compliance with the destination server.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] All modern browsers designate requests with custom headers as "to be preflighted".
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] When the API verifies that the custom header is there, you know that the request must have been preflighted if it came from a browser.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Cookies are not set on cross-origin requests (CORS) by default.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] To enable cookies on an API, you will set `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials=true`.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The browser will reject any response that includes `Access-Control-Allow-Origin=*` if credentials are allowed.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] To allow CORS requests, but protect against CSRF, you need to make sure the server only allows a few select origins that you definitively control via the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` header.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Any cross-origin request from an allowed domain will be able to set custom headers.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] A less secure configuration would be to configure your backend server to allow CORS from all subdomains of your site using a regular expression.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If an attacker is able to take over a subdomain (not uncommon with cloud services) your CORS configuration would allow them to bypass the same origin policy and forge a request with your custom header.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side CSRF is a new variant of CSRF attacks where the attacker tricks the client-side JavaScript code to send a forged HTTP request to a vulnerable target site by manipulating the program's input parameters.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side CSRF originates when the JavaScript program uses attacker-controlled inputs, such as the URL, for the generation of asynchronous HTTP requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information about client-side CSRF vulnerabilities, see Sections 2 and 5 of this paper, the CSRF chapter of the SameSite wiki, and this post by the Meta Bug Bounty Program.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The following code snippet demonstrates a simple example of a client-side CSRF vulnerability.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For more examples of client-side CSRF, see this post by the Meta Bug Bounty Program and this USENIX Security paper.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] SameSite is a cookie attribute (similar to HTTPOnly, Secure etc.) which aims to mitigate CSRF attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This attribute helps the browser decide whether to send cookies along with cross-site requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Possible values for this attribute are `Lax`, `Strict`, or `None`.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The Strict value will prevent the cookie from being sent by the browser to the target site in all cross-site browsing context, even when following a regular link.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, if a GitHub-like website uses the Strict value, a logged-in GitHub user who tries to follow a link to a private GitHub project posted on a corporate discussion forum or email, the user will not be able to access the project because GitHub will not receive a session cookie.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Since a bank website would not allow any transactional pages to be linked from external sites, so the Strict flag would be most appropriate for banks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If a website wants to maintain a user's logged-in session after the user arrives from an external link, SameSite's default Lax value provides a reasonable balance between security and usability.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the GitHub scenario above uses a Lax value instead, the session cookie would be allowed when following a regular link from an external website while blocking it in CSRF-prone request methods such as POST.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Only cross-site-requests that are allowed in Lax mode have top-level navigations and use safe HTTP methods.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For more details on the `SameSite` values, check the following section from the rfc.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] All modern desktop and mobile browsers support the `SameSite` attribute.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The main exceptions are legacy browsers including Opera Mini (all versions), UC Browser for Android, and older mobile browsers (iOS Safari < 13.2, Android Browser < 97).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] To track the browsers implementing it and know how the attribute is used, refer to the following service.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Chrome implemented `SameSite=Lax` as the default behavior in 2020, and Firefox and Edge have followed suit.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, the `Secure` flag is required for cookies that are marked as `SameSite=None`.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] `SameSite` is useful as a defense-in-depth control but it does not replace a proper CSRF defense in most deployments.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For any application that does not meet all of the above, `SameSite` should be treated as a defense-in-depth layer and combined with a CSRF token or a double-submit pattern rather than relied on alone.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Determining the origin that the request is going to (target origin).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] At server-side, we verify if both of them match.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If they do, we accept the request as legitimate (meaning it's the same origin request) and if they don't, we discard the request (meaning that the request originated from cross-domain).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Reliability on these headers comes from the fact that they cannot be altered programmatically as they fall under forbidden headers list, meaning that only the browser can set them.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the Origin header is present, verify that its value matches the target origin.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Unlike the referer, the Origin header will be present in HTTP requests that originate from an HTTPS URL.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If the Origin header is not present, verify that the hostname in the Referer header matches the target origin.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This method of CSRF mitigation is also commonly used with unauthenticated requests, such as requests made prior to establishing a session state, which is required to keep track of a synchronization token.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In both cases, make sure the target origin check is strong.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, if your site is `example.org` make sure `example.org.attacker.com` does not pass your origin check (i.e, match through the trailing / after the origin to make sure you are matching against the entire origin).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If neither of these headers are present, you can either accept or block the request.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, you might want to log all such instances, monitor their use cases/behavior, and then start blocking requests only after you get enough confidence.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Generally, it's not always easy to determine the target origin.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] You are not always able to simply grab the target origin (i.e., its hostname and port `#`) from the URL in the request, because the application server is frequently sitting behind one or more proxies.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This means that the original URL can be different from the URL the app server actually receives.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] However, if your application server is directly accessed by its users, then using the origin in the URL is fine and you're all set.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] If you are behind a proxy, there are a number of options to consider.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Using this header value for mitigation will work properly when origin or referrer headers are present in the requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Though these headers are included the **majority** of the time, there are few use cases where they are not included (most of them are for legitimate reasons to safeguard users privacy/to tune to browsers ecosystem).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Usually, a minor percentage of traffic does fall under above categories (1-2%) and no enterprise would want to lose this traffic.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] One of the popular technique used across the Internet to make this technique more usable is to accept the request if the Origin/referrer matches your configured list of domains "OR" a null value (Examples here.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The null value is to cover the edge cases mentioned above where these headers are not sent).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Please note that, attackers can exploit this but people prefer to use this technique as a defense in depth measure because of the minor effort involved in deploying it.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] While the `SameSite` and `Secure` attributes mentioned earlier restrict the sending of already set cookies and `HttpOnly` restricts the reading of a set cookie, an attacker may still try to inject or overwrite otherwise secured cookies (cf. session fixation attacks).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Using `Cookie Prefixes` for cookies with CSRF tokens extends security protections against this kind of attacks as well.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In addition to the `__Host-` prefix, the weaker `__Secure-` prefix is also supported by browser vendors.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This relaxed variant can be used as an alternative to the "domain locked" `__Host-` prefix, if authenticated users would need to visit different (sub-)domains.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] In all other cases, using the `__Host-` prefix in addition to the `SameSite` attribute is recommended.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Cookie prefixes are supported by all major browsers.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Mozilla Developer Network and IETF Draft for further information about cookie prefixes.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] While all the techniques referenced here do not require any user interaction, sometimes it's easier or more appropriate to involve the user in the transaction to prevent unauthorized operations (forged via CSRF or otherwise).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] The following are some examples of techniques that can act as strong CSRF defense when implemented correctly.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Do NOT use CAPTCHA because it is specifically designed to protect against bots.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] It is possible, and still valid in some implementations of CAPTCHA, to obtain proof of human interaction/presence from a different user session.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Although this makes the CSRF exploit more complex, it does not protect against it.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] While these are very strong CSRF defenses, it can create a significant impact on the user experience.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] As such, they would generally only be used for security critical operations (such as password changes, money transfers, etc.), alongside the other defences discussed in this cheat sheet.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Most developers tend to ignore CSRF vulnerabilities on login forms as they assume that CSRF would not be applicable on login forms because user is not authenticated at that stage, however this assumption is not always true.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] CSRF vulnerabilities can still occur on login forms where the user is not authenticated, but the impact and risk is different.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, if an attacker uses CSRF to assume an authenticated identity of a target victim on a shopping website using the attacker's account, and the victim then enters their credit card information, an attacker may be able to purchase items using the victim's stored card details.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] For more information about login CSRF and other risks, see section 3 of this paper.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Login CSRF can be mitigated by creating pre-sessions (sessions before a user is authenticated) and including tokens in login form.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] You can use any of the techniques mentioned above to generate tokens.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Remember that pre-sessions cannot be transitioned to real sessions once the user is authenticated - the session should be destroyed and a new one should be made to avoid session fixation attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] This technique is described in Robust Defenses for Cross-Site Request Forgery section 4.1.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p01] Login CSRF can also be mitigated by including a custom request headers in AJAX request as described above.
