[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] The following guidance for JavaScript by default considers **GET**, **HEAD** and **OPTIONS** methods as safe operations.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Therefore **GET**, **HEAD**, and **OPTIONS** method AJAX calls need not be appended with a CSRF token header.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] However, if the verbs are used to perform state changing operations, they will also require a CSRF token header (although this is a bad practice, and should be avoided).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] The **POST**, **PUT**, **PATCH**, and **DELETE** methods, being state changing verbs, should have a CSRF token attached to the request.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] The following guidance will demonstrate how to create overrides in JavaScript libraries to have CSRF tokens included automatically with every AJAX request for the state changing methods mentioned above.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] A CSRF token can be included in the `<meta>` tag as shown below.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] All subsequent calls in the page can extract the CSRF token from this `<meta>` tag.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] It can also be stored in a JavaScript variable or anywhere on the DOM.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] However, it is not recommended to store the CSRF token in cookies or browser local storage.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] The exact syntax of populating the content attribute would depend on your web application's backend programming language.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Several JavaScript libraries allow you to override default settings to have a header added automatically to all AJAX requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] XMLHttpRequest's open() method can be overridden to set the `X-CSRF-Token` header whenever the `open()` method is invoked next.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] The function `csrfSafeMethod()` defined below will filter out the safe HTTP methods and only add the header to unsafe HTTP methods.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Modern Single Page Application (SPA) frameworks like Angular, React, and Vue typically rely on the cookie-to-header pattern to mitigate Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] This approach leverages the fact that browsers automatically attach cookies to cross-origin requests, but only JavaScript running on the same origin can read values and set custom headers—making it possible to detect and block forged requests.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Client reads the token: The SPA (often using a library like Angular's HttpClient or axios in React/Vue) reads the CSRF token from the cookie.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Client attaches the token to a custom header: For each state-changing request (`POST`, `PUT`, `DELETE`, etc.), the client sets the token as a custom HTTP header (commonly `X-XSRF-TOKEN` or `X-CSRF-TOKEN`).
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Server validates the token: The server checks whether the token from the header matches the one from the cookie.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] If they match, the request is accepted; if not, it is rejected as potentially forged.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Angular provides this pattern out of the box, automatically handling steps 2 and 3 via its HttpClient.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] In contrast, frameworks like React and Vue require developers to implement this logic manually or with helper libraries such as axios interceptors.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] This pattern ensures that even if a browser includes cookies with a forged request, the attacker cannot set the matching custom header from another origin.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Angular's HttpClient supports the Cookie-to-Header Pattern used to prevent XSRF attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] When performing HTTP requests, an interceptor reads a token from a cookie, by default `XSRF-TOKEN`, and sets it as an HTTP header, `X-XSRF-TOKEN`.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Further documentation can be found at Angular's documentation for HttpClient XSRF/CSRF security.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] This code snippet has been tested with Angular version 19.2.11.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Axios allows us to set default headers for the POST, PUT, DELETE and PATCH actions.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] This code snippet has been tested with Axios version 1.9.0.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] JQuery exposes an API called `$.ajaxSetup()` which can be used to add the `X-CSRF-Token` header to the AJAX request.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] API documentation for `$.ajaxSetup()` can be found here.
