[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] This code snippet has been tested with jQuery version 3.7.1.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] TypeScript allows you to create strongly typed utilities for CSRF protection.
[src:security/cross-site-request-forgery-prevention-cheat-sheet-p02] Angular is built with TypeScript, making it a natural fit for strongly-typed CSRF protection.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet helps developers prevent XSS vulnerabilities.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) is a misnomer.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Originally this term was derived from early versions of the attack that were primarily focused on stealing data cross-site.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Since then, the term has widened to include injection of basically any content.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] XSS attacks are serious and can lead to account impersonation, observing user behaviour, loading external content, stealing sensitive data, and more.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Fortunately, applications built with modern web frameworks have fewer XSS bugs, because these frameworks steer developers towards good security practices and help mitigate XSS by using templating, auto-escaping, and more.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] When you use a modern web framework, you need to know how your framework prevents XSS and where it has gaps.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] There will be times where you need to do something outside the protection provided by your framework, which means that Output Encoding and HTML Sanitization can be critical.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] OWASP will be producing framework specific cheatsheets for React, Vue, and Angular.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] In order for an XSS attack to be successful, an attacker must be able to insert and execute malicious content in a webpage.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Thus, all variables in a web application needs to be protected.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Ensuring that **all variables** go through validation and are then escaped or sanitized is known as **perfect injection resistance**.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Any variable that does not go through this process is a potential weakness.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Frameworks make it easy to ensure variables are correctly validated and escaped or sanitised.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] However, no framework is perfect and security gaps still exist in popular frameworks like React and Angular.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Output encoding and HTML sanitization help address those gaps.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] When you need to safely display data exactly as a user types it in, output encoding is recommended.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Variables should not be interpreted as code instead of text.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This section covers each form of output encoding, where to use it, and when you should not use dynamic variables at all.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] First, when you wish to display data as the user typed it in, start with your framework’s default output encoding protection.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Automatic encoding and escaping functions are built into most frameworks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you’re not using a framework or need to cover gaps in the framework then you should use an output encoding library.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Each variable used in the user interface should be passed through an output encoding function.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] A list of output encoding libraries is included in the appendix.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] There are many different output encoding methods because browsers parse HTML, JS, URLs, and CSS differently.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Using the wrong encoding method may introduce weaknesses or harm the functionality of your application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] “HTML Context” refers to inserting a variable between two basic HTML tags like a `<div>` or `<b>`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] An attacker could modify data that is rendered as `$varUnsafe`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This could lead to an attack being added to a webpage.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] In order to add a variable to a HTML context safely to a web template, use HTML entity encoding for that variable.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you're using JavaScript for writing to HTML, look at the `.textContent` attribute.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] It is a **Safe Sink** and will automatically HTML Entity Encode.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] “HTML Attribute Contexts” occur when a variable is placed in an HTML attribute value.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] You may want to do this to change a hyperlink, hide an element, add alt-text for an image, or change inline CSS styles.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] You should apply HTML attribute encoding to variables being placed in most HTML attributes.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] A list of safe HTML attributes is provided in the **Safe Sinks** section.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you're writing to a HTML Attribute with JavaScript, look at the `.setAttribute` and `[attribute]` methods because they will automatically HTML Attribute Encode.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Those are **Safe Sinks** as long as the attribute name is hardcoded and innocuous, like `id` or `class`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Generally, attributes that accept JavaScript, such as `onClick`, are **NOT safe** to use with untrusted attribute values.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] “JavaScript Contexts” refers to the situation where variables are placed into inline JavaScript and then embedded in an HTML document.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This situation commonly occurs in programs that heavily use custom JavaScript that is embedded in their web pages.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] However, the only ‘safe’ location for placing variables in JavaScript is inside a “quoted data value”.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] All other contexts are unsafe and you should not place variable data in them.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encode all characters using the `\xHH` format.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding libraries often have a `EncodeForJavaScript` or similar to support this function.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Please look at the OWASP Java Encoder JavaScript encoding examples for examples of proper JavaScript use that requires minimal encoding.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] For JSON, verify that the `Content-Type` header is `application/json` and not `text/html` to prevent XSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] “CSS Contexts” refer to variables placed into inline CSS, which is common when developers want their users to customize the look and feel of their webpages.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Since CSS is surprisingly powerful, it has been used for many types of attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] **Variables should only be placed in a CSS property value.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you're using JavaScript to change a CSS property, look into using `style.property = x`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This is a **Safe Sink** and will automatically CSS encode data in it.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] When inserting variables into CSS properties, ensure the data is properly encoded and sanitized to prevent injection attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Avoid placing variables directly into selectors or other CSS contexts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] “URL Contexts” refer to variables placed into a URL.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Most commonly, a developer will add a parameter or URL fragment to a URL base that is then displayed or used in some operation.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encode all characters with the `%HH` encoding format.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Make sure any attributes are fully quoted, same as JS and CSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] There will be situations where you use a URL in different contexts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The most common one would be adding it to an `href` or `src` attribute of an `<a>` tag.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] In these scenarios, you should do URL encoding, followed by HTML attribute encoding.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you're using JavaScript to construct a URL Query Value, look into using `window.encodeURIComponent(x)`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This is a **Safe Sink** and will automatically URL encode data in it.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] These locations are known as **dangerous contexts**.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Don't place variables into dangerous contexts as even with output encoding, it will not prevent an XSS attack fully.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] When users need to author HTML, developers may let users change the styling or structure of content inside a WYSIWYG editor.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Output encoding in this case will prevent XSS, but it will break the intended functionality of the application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] In these cases, HTML Sanitization should be used.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] HTML Sanitization will strip dangerous HTML from a variable and return a safe string of HTML.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] OWASP recommends DOMPurify for HTML Sanitization.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Security professionals often talk in terms of sources and sinks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] If you pollute a river, it'll flow downstream somewhere.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] XSS sinks are places where variables are placed into your webpage.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Thankfully, many sinks where variables can be placed are safe.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This is because these sinks treat the variable as text and will never execute it.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Try to refactor your code to remove references to unsafe sinks like innerHTML, and instead use textContent or value.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] For attributes not reported above, ensure that if JavaScript code is provided as a value, it cannot be executed.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Framework Security Protections, Output Encoding, and HTML Sanitization will provide the best protection for your application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] OWASP recommends these in all circumstances.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Consider adopting the following controls in addition to the above.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] These snippets of HTML demonstrate how to render untrusted data safely in a variety of different contexts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Data Type: String Context: GET Parameter Code: `<a href="/site/search?value=UNTRUSTED DATA ">clickme</a>` Sample Defense: URL Encoding (rule #5).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Data Type: String Context: CSS Value Code: `HTML <div style="width: UNTRUSTED DATA ;">Selection</div>` Sample Defense: Strict structural validation (rule #4), CSS hex encoding, Good design of CSS features.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Data Type: HTML Context: HTML Body Code: `<div>UNTRUSTED HTML</div>` Sample Defense: HTML validation (JSoup, AntiSamy, HTML Sanitizer...).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The purpose of output encoding (as it relates to Cross Site Scripting) is to convert untrusted input into a safe form where the input is displayed as **data** to the user without executing as **code** in the browser.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The following charts provides a list of critical output encoding methods needed to stop Cross Site Scripting.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding Type: HTML Attribute Encoding Encoding Mechanism: Encode all characters with the HTML Entity `&#xHH;` format, including spaces, where **HH** represents the hexadecimal value of the character in Unicode.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] All alphanumeric characters (letters A to Z, a to z, and digits 0 to 9) remain unencoded.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding Type: URL Encoding Encoding Mechanism: Use standard percent encoding, as specified in the W3C specification, to encode parameter values.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Be cautious and only encode parameter values, not the entire URL or path fragments of a URL.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding Type: JavaScript Encoding Encoding Mechanism: Encode all characters using the Unicode `\uXXXX` encoding format, where **XXXX** represents the hexadecimal Unicode code point.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Encoding Type: CSS Hex Encoding Encoding Mechanism: CSS encoding supports both `\XX` and `\XXXXXX` formats.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] To ensure proper encoding, consider these options: (a) Add a space after the CSS encode (which will be ignored by the CSS parser), or (b) use the full six-character CSS encoding format by zero-padding the value.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Alphanumeric characters (letters A to Z, a to z, and digits 0 to 9) remain unencoded.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] For that reason, some have sought shortcuts to preventing XSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] We're going to examine two common anti-patterns that frequently show up in ancient posts, but are still commonly cited as solutions in modern posts about XSS defense on programmer forums such as Stack Overflow and other developer hangouts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] First, let us be clear, we are a strong proponent of CSP when it is used properly.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] What we are against is a blanket CSP policy for the entire enterprise.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] There usually is an implicit assumption that all the customer browsers support all the CSP constructs that your blanket CSP policy is using.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Furthermore, this assumption often is done without testing the explicitly the `User-Agent` request header to see if it indeed is a supported browser type and rejecting the use of the site if it is not.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Because most businesses don't want to turn away customers if they are using an outdated browser that doesn't support some CSP Level 2 or Level 3 construct that they are relying on for XSS prevention.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Mandatory universal enterprise-wide CSP response headers are inevitably going to break some web applications, especially legacy ones.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This causes the business to push-back against AppSec guidelines and inevitably results in AppSec issuing waivers and/or security exceptions until the application code can be patched up.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] But these security exceptions allow cracks in your XSS armor, and even if the cracks are temporary they still can impact your business, at least on a reputational basis.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] While this can be successful for very specific applications (for instance, if you validate that all the input requests that are ever rendered are only alphanumeric data), it violates the major tenet of XSS defense where perform output encoding as close to where the data is rendered is possible.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Generally, the HTTP request is examined for query and POST parameters but other things HTTP request headers that might be rendered such as cookie data, are not examined.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The common approach that we've seen is someone will call either `ESAPI.validator().getValidSafeHTML()` or `ESAPI.encoder.canonicalize()` and depending on the results will redirect to an error page or call something like `ESAPI.encoder().encodeForHTML()`.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Aside from the fact that this approach often misses tainted input such as request headers or "extra path information" in a URI, the approach completely ignores the fact that the output encoding is completely non-contextual.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] For example, how does a servlet filter know that an input query parameter is going to be rendered in an HTML context (i.e., between HTML tags) rather than in a JavaScript context such as within a `<script>` tag or used with a JavaScript event handler attribute?
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] And because JavaScript and HTML encoding are not interchangeable, you leave yourself still open to XSS attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Unless your filter or interceptor has full knowledge of your application and specifically an awareness of how your application uses each parameter for a given request, it can't succeed for all the possible edge cases.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] And we would contend that it never will be able to using this approach because providing that additional required context is way too complex of a design and accidentally introducing some other vulnerability (possibly one whose impact is far worse than XSS) is almost inevitable if you attempt it.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] This naive approach usually has at least one of these four problems.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] One problem is the improper encoding that can still allow exploitable XSS in some URI paths of your application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] A second problem with this approach can be the application can result in incorrect or double encoding.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] E.g., suppose in the previous example, a developer has done proper output encoding for the JavaScript rendering of lastname.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] But if it is already been HTML output encoded too, when it is rendered, a legitimate last name like "O'Hara" might come out rendered like "O\'Hara".
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The third problem with this is that it is not effective against DOM-based XSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] To do that, one would have to have an interceptor or filter scan all the JavaScript content going as part of an HTTP response, try to figure out the tainted output and see if it it is susceptible to DOM-based XSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The last problem with interceptors is that they generally are oblivious to data in your application's responses that originate from other internal sources such as an internal REST-based web service or even an internal database.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The problem is that unless your application is strictly validating that data *at the point that it is retrieved* (which generally is the only point your application has enough context to do a strict data validation using an allow-list approach), that data should always be considered tainted.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] The approach that generally is used on response-side interceptors attempting to provide XSS defense has been to only consider the matching "input parameters" as tainted and do output encoding or HTML sanitization on them and everything else is considered safe.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] While it frequently is assumed that all internal web services and all internal databases can be "trusted" and used as it, this is a very bad assumption to make unless you have included that in some deep threat modeling for your application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] For example, suppose you are working on an application to show a customer their detailed monthly bill.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Let's assume that your application is either querying a foreign (as in not part of your specific application) internal database or REST web service that your application uses to obtain the user's full name, address, etc.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] But that data originates from another application which you are assuming is "trusted" but actually has an unreported persistent XSS vulnerability on the various customer address-related fields.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Furthermore, let's assume that you company's customer support staff can examine a customer's detailed bill to assist them when customers have questions about their bills.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] So nefarious customer decides to plant an XSS bomb in the address field and then calls customer service for assistance with the bill.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] Should a scenario like that ever play out, an interceptor attempting to prevent XSS is going to miss that completely and the result is going to be something much worse than just popping an alert box to display "1" or "XSS" or "pwn'd".
[src:security/cross-site-scripting-prevention-cheat-sheet] One final note: If deploying interceptors / filters as an XSS defense was a useful approach against XSS attacks, don't you think that it would be incorporated into all commercial Web Application Firewalls (WAFs) and be an approach that OWASP recommends in this cheat sheet?
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] OWASP considers the term cross-site scripting to be a misnomer.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] It initially was an attack that was used for breaching data across sites, but gradually started to include other forms of data injection attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Security on the web depends on a variety of mechanisms, including an underlying concept of trust known as the same-origin policy.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Content from URLs where any of these three attributes are different will have to be granted permissions separately.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks use known vulnerabilities in web-based applications, their servers, or the plug-in systems on which they rely.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Exploiting one of these, attackers fold malicious content into the content being delivered from the compromised site.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] When the resulting combined content arrives at the client-side web browser, it has all been delivered from the trusted source, and thus operates under the permissions granted to that system.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] By finding ways of injecting malicious scripts into web pages, an attacker can gain elevated access-privileges to sensitive page content, to session cookies, and to a variety of other information maintained by the browser on behalf of the user.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting attacks are a case of code injection.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Microsoft security-engineers introduced the term "cross-site scripting" in January 2000.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The definition gradually expanded to encompass other modes of code injection, including persistent and non-JavaScript vectors (including ActiveX, Java, VBScript, Flash, or even HTML scripts), causing some confusion to newcomers to the field of information security.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities have been reported and exploited since the 1990s.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Prominent sites affected in the past include the social-networking sites Twitter and Facebook.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Cross-site scripting flaws have since surpassed buffer overflows to become the most common publicly reported security vulnerability, with some researchers in 2007 estimating as many as 68% of websites are likely open to XSS attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] There is no single, standardized classification of cross-site scripting flaws, but most experts distinguish between at least two primary flavors of XSS flaws: *non-persistent* and *persistent*.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Some sources further divide these two groups into *traditional* (caused by server-side code flaws) and *DOM-based* (in client-side code).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The *non-persistent* (or *reflected*) cross-site scripting vulnerability is by far the most basic type of web vulnerability.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] These holes show up when the data provided by a web client, most commonly in HTTP query parameters (e.g.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] HTML form submission), is used immediately by server-side scripts to parse and display a page of results for that user, without properly sanitizing the content.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Because HTML documents have a flat, serial structure that mixes control statements, formatting, and the actual content, any non-validated user-supplied data included in the resulting page without proper HTML encoding, may lead to markup injection.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of a potential vector is a site search engine: if one searches for a string, the search string will typically be redisplayed verbatim on the result page to indicate what was searched for.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] If this response does not properly escape or reject HTML control characters, a cross-site scripting flaw will ensue.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] A reflected attack is typically delivered via email or a neutral web site.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The bait is an innocent-looking URL, pointing to a trusted site but containing the XSS vector.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] If the trusted site is vulnerable to the vector, clicking the link can cause the victim's browser to execute the injected script.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] A classic example of this is with online message boards where users are allowed to post HTML formatted messages for other users to read.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] For example, suppose there is a dating website where members scan the profiles of other members to see if they look interesting.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] For privacy reasons, this site hides everybody's real name and email.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The only time a member's real name and email are in the browser is when the member is signed in, and they can't see anyone else's.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Suppose that Mallory, an attacker, joins the site and wants to figure out the real names of the people she sees on the site.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] To do so, she writes a script designed to run from other users' browsers when *they* visit *her* profile.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The script then sends a quick message to her own server, which collects this information.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] To do this, for the question "Describe your Ideal First Date", Mallory gives a short answer (to appear normal), but the text at the end of her answer is her script to steal names and emails.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] If the script is enclosed inside a `<script>` element, it won't be shown on the screen.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Then suppose that Bob, a member of the dating site, reaches Mallory's profile, which has her answer to the First Date question.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Her script is run automatically by the browser and steals a copy of Bob's real name and email directly from his own machine.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Persistent XSS vulnerabilities can be more significant than other types because an attacker's malicious script is rendered automatically, without the need to individually target victims or lure them to a third-party website.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Particularly in the case of social networking sites, the code would be further designed to self-propagate across accounts, creating a type of client-side worm.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The methods of injection can vary a great deal; in some cases, the attacker may not even need to directly interact with the web functionality itself to exploit such a hole.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Any data received by the web application (via email, system logs, IM etc.) that can be controlled by an attacker could become an injection vector.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] XSS vulnerabilities were originally found in applications that performed all data processing on the server side.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] User input (including an XSS vector) would be sent to the server, and then sent back to the user as a web page.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The need for an improved user experience resulted in popularity of applications that had a majority of the presentation logic (maybe written in JavaScript) working on the client-side that pulled data, on-demand, from the server using AJAX.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] As the JavaScript code was also processing user input and rendering it in the web page content, a new sub-class of reflected XSS attacks started to appear that was called *DOM-based cross-site scripting*.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] In a DOM-based XSS attack, the malicious data does not touch the web server.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Rather, it is being reflected by the JavaScript code, fully on the client side.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] An example of a DOM-based XSS vulnerability is the bug found in 2011 in a number of jQuery plugins.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Prevention strategies for DOM-based XSS attacks include very similar measures to traditional XSS prevention strategies but implemented in JavaScript code and contained in web pages (i.e. input validation and escaping).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Some JavaScript frameworks have built-in countermeasures against this and other types of attack — for example AngularJS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Self-XSS is a form of XSS vulnerability that relies on social engineering in order to trick the victim into executing malicious JavaScript code in their browser.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Although it is technically not a true XSS vulnerability due to the fact it relies on socially engineering a user into executing code rather than a flaw in the affected website allowing an attacker to do so, it still poses the same risks as a regular XSS vulnerability if properly executed.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Mutated XSS happens when the attacker injects something that is seemingly safe but is rewritten and modified by the browser while parsing the markup.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] This makes it extremely hard to detect or sanitize within the website's application logic.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] An example is rebalancing unclosed quotation marks or even adding quotation marks to unquoted values in CSS font-family properties.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] There are several escaping schemes that can be used depending on where the untrusted string needs to be placed within an HTML document including HTML entity encoding, JavaScript escaping, CSS escaping, and URL (or percent) encoding.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Most web applications that do not need to accept rich data can use escaping to largely eliminate the risk of XSS attacks in a fairly straightforward manner.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Performing HTML entity encoding only on the five XML significant characters is not always sufficient to prevent many forms of XSS attacks, security encoding libraries are usually easier to use.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Some web template systems understand the structure of the HTML they produce and automatically pick an appropriate encoder.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Many operators of particular web applications (e.g. forums and webmail) allow users to utilize HTML markup.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] When accepting HTML input from users (say, `<b>very</b> large`), output encoding (such as `&lt;b&gt;very&lt;/b&gt; large`) will not suffice since the user input needs to be rendered as HTML by the browser (so it shows as `**very** large`, instead of `<b>very</b> large`).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Stopping an XSS attack when accepting HTML input from users is much more complex in this situation.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Often, untrusted HTML input must be run through an HTML sanitization engine to ensure that it does not contain potentially malicious JavaScript code.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Many validations rely on parsing out (blacklisting) specific "at risk" HTML tags such as the `<iframe>`, `<link>`, and `<script>` tag, or by only allowing certain tags and removing or escaping others.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Another popular method is to strip user input of " and ' however this can also be bypassed as the payload can be concealed with obfuscation.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Besides content filtering, other imperfect methods for cross-site scripting mitigation are also commonly used.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] One example is the use of additional security controls when handling cookie-based user authentication.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Many web applications rely on session cookies for authentication between individual HTTP requests, and because client-side scripts generally have access to these cookies, simple XSS exploits can steal these cookies.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] To mitigate this particular threat (though not the XSS problem in general), many web applications tie session cookies to the IP address of the user who originally logged in, then only permit that IP to use that cookie.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] This is effective in most situations (if an attacker is only after the cookie), but obviously breaks down in situations where an attacker is behind the same NATed IP address or web proxy as the victim, or the victim is changing his or her mobile IP.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Another mitigation present in Internet Explorer (since version 6), Firefox (since version 2.0.0.5), Safari (since version 4), Opera (since version 9.5) and Google Chrome, is an *HttpOnly* flag which allows a web server to set a cookie that is unavailable to client-side scripts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] While beneficial, the feature can neither fully prevent cookie theft nor prevent attacks within the browser.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] While Web 2.0 and Ajax developers require the use of JavaScript, some web applications are written to allow operation without the need for any client-side scripts.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] This allows users, if they choose, to disable scripting in their browsers before using the application.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] In this way, even potentially malicious client-side scripts could be inserted unescaped on a page, and users would not be susceptible to XSS attacks.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Some browsers or browser plugins can be configured to disable client-side scripts on a per-domain basis.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] This approach is of limited value if scripting is allowed by default, since it blocks bad sites only *after* the user knows that they are bad, which is too late.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Functionality that blocks all scripting and external inclusions by default and then allows the user to enable it on a per-domain basis is more effective.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] This has been possible for a long time in Internet Explorer (since version 4) by setting up its so called "Security Zones", and in Opera (since version 9) using its "Site Specific Preferences".
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] A solution for Firefox and other Gecko-based browsers is the open source NoScript add-on which, in addition to the ability to enable scripts on a per-domain basis, provides some XSS protection even when scripts are enabled.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Another problem with script blocking is that many users do not understand it, and do not know how to properly secure their browsers.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Yet another drawback is that many sites do not work without client-side scripting, forcing users to disable protection for that site and opening their systems to vulnerabilities.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The Firefox NoScript extension enables users to allow scripts selectively from a given page while disallowing others on the same page.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] For example, scripts from example.com could be allowed, while scripts from advertisingagency.com that are attempting to run on the same page could be disallowed.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types changes Web APIs to check that values have been trademarked as trusted.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] As long as programs only trademark trustworthy values, an attacker who controls a JavaScript string value cannot cause XSS.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Trusted types are designed to be auditable by blue teams.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] Another defense approach is to use automated tools that will remove XSS malicious code in web pages, these tools use static analysis and/or pattern matching methods to identify malicious codes potentially and secure them using methods like escaping.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] When a cookie is set with the `SameSite=Strict` parameter, it is stripped from all cross-origin requests.
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] When set with `SameSite=Lax`, it is stripped from all non-"safe" cross-origin requests (that is, requests other than GET, OPTIONS, and TRACE which have read-only semantics).
[src:security/cross-site-scripting] The feature is implemented in Google Chrome since version 63 and Firefox since version 60.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This article is focused on providing clear, simple, actionable guidance for providing Input Validation security functionality in your applications.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation is performed to ensure only properly formed data is entering the workflow in an information system, preventing malformed data from persisting in the database and triggering malfunction of various downstream components.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation should happen as early as possible in the data flow, preferably as soon as the data is received from the external party.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Data from all potentially untrusted sources should be subject to input validation, including not only Internet-facing web clients but also backend feeds over extranets, from suppliers, partners, vendors or regulators, each of which may be compromised on their own and start sending malformed data.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input Validation should not be used as the *primary* method of preventing XSS, SQL Injection and other attacks which are covered in respective cheat sheets but can significantly contribute to reducing their impact if implemented properly.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is always recommended to prevent attacks as early as possible in the processing of the user's (attacker's) request.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation can be used to detect unauthorized input before it is processed by the application.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is a common mistake to use denylist validation in order to try to detect possibly dangerous characters and patterns like the apostrophe `'` character, the string `1=1`, or the `<script>` tag, but this is a massively flawed approach as it is trivial for an attacker to bypass such filters.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Plus, such filters frequently prevent authorized input, like `O'Brian`, where the `'` character is fully legitimate.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For more information on XSS filter evasion please see this wiki page.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] While denylisting can be useful as an additional layer of defense to catch some common malicious patterns, it should not be relied upon as the primary method.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlisting remains the more robust and secure approach for preventing potentially harmful input.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlist validation is appropriate for all input fields provided by the user.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Allowlist validation involves defining exactly what IS authorized, and by definition, everything else is not authorized.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If it's well structured data, like dates, social security numbers, zip codes, email addresses, etc. then the developer should be able to define a very strong validation pattern, usually based on regular expressions, for validating such input.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If the input field comes from a fixed set of options, like a drop down list or radio buttons, then the input needs to match exactly one of the values offered to the user in the first place.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Any failure to validate a value against this discrete list of options on the server side is a high security event and should be logged as a high severity event as it indicates that an attacker is tampering with the client-side code.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Free-form text, especially with Unicode characters, is perceived as difficult to validate due to a relatively large space of characters that need to be allowed.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It's also free-form text input that highlights the importance of proper context-aware output encoding and quite clearly demonstrates that input validation is **not** the primary safeguards against Cross-Site Scripting.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If your users want to type apostrophe `'` or less-than sign `<` in their comment field, they might have perfectly legitimate reason for that and the application's job is to properly handle it throughout the whole life cycle of the data.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Developing regular expressions can be complicated, and is well beyond the scope of this cheat sheet.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] There are lots of resources on the internet about how to write regular expressions, including this site and the OWASP Validation Regex Repository.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] When designing regular expressions, be aware of RegEx Denial of Service (ReDoS) attacks.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] These attacks cause a program using a poorly designed Regular Expression to operate very slowly and utilize CPU resources for a very long time.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Example validating the parameter "zip" using a regular expression.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Some Allowlist validators have also been predefined in various open source packages that you can leverage.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Input validation **must** be implemented on the server-side before any data is processed by an application’s functions, as any JavaScript-based input validation performed on the client-side can be circumvented by an attacker who disables JavaScript or uses a web proxy.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Implementing both client-side JavaScript-based validation for UX and server-side validation for security is the recommended approach, leveraging each for their respective strengths.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] It is very difficult to validate rich content submitted by a user.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For more information, please see the XSS cheat sheet on Sanitizing HTML Markup with a Library Designed for the Job.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] All user data controlled must be encoded when returned in the HTML page to prevent the execution of malicious data (e.g.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The type of encoding is specific to the context of the page where the user controlled data is inserted.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] For example, HTML entity encoding is appropriate for data placed into the HTML body.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] However, user data placed into a script would need JavaScript specific output encoding.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Many websites allow users to upload files, such as a profile picture or more.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This section helps provide that feature securely.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The upload feature should be using an allowlist approach to only allow specific file types and extensions.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The format of email addresses is defined by RFC 5321, and is far more complicated than most people realise.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Properly parsing email addresses for validity with regular expressions is very complicated, although there are a number of publicly available documents on regex.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The biggest caveat on this is that although the RFC defines a very flexible format for email addresses, most real world implementations (such as mail servers) use a far more restricted address format, meaning that they will reject addresses that are *technically* valid.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Although they may be technically correct, these addresses are of little use if your application will not be able to actually send emails to them.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] As such, the best way to validate email addresses is to perform some basic initial validation, and then pass the address to the mail server and catch the exception if it rejects it.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This means that the application can be confident that its mail server can send emails to any addresses it accepts.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Semantic validation is about determining whether the email address is correct and legitimate.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The most common way to do this is to send an email to the user, and require that they click a link in the email, or enter a code that has been sent to them.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] After validating the ownership of the email address, the user should then be required to authenticate on the application through the usual mechanism.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] In some cases, users may not want to give their real email address when registering on the application, and will instead provide a disposable email address.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] These are publicly available addresses that do not require the user to authenticate, and are typically used to reduce the amount of spam received by users' primary email addresses.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Blocking disposable email addresses is almost impossible, as there are a large number of websites offering these services, with new domains being created every day.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] There are a number of publicly available lists and commercial lists of known disposable domains, but these will always be incomplete.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If these lists are used to block the use of disposable email addresses then the user should be presented with a message explaining why they are blocked (although they are likely to simply search for another disposable provider rather than giving their legitimate address).
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] If it is essential that disposable email addresses are blocked, then registrations should only be allowed from specifically-allowed email providers.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] However, if this includes public providers such as Google or Yahoo, users can simply register their own disposable address with them.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Sub-addressing allows a user to specify a *tag* in the local part of the email address (before the `@` sign), which will be ignored by the mail server.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Many mail providers (such as Microsoft Exchange) do not support sub-addressing.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] The most notable provider who does is Gmail, although there are many others that also do.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Some users will use a different *tag* for each website they register on, so that if they start receiving spam to one of the sub-addresses they can identify which website leaked or sold their email address.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Because it could allow users to register multiple accounts with a single email address, some sites may wish to block sub-addressing by stripping out everything between the `+` and `@` signs.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] This is not generally recommended, as it suggests that the website owner is either unaware of sub-addressing or wishes to prevent users from identifying them when they leak or sell email addresses.
[src:security/input-validation-cheat-sheet] Additionally, it can be trivially bypassed by using disposable email addresses, or simply registering multiple email accounts with a trusted provider.
[src:security/json-web-token] For example, a server could generate a token that has the claim "logged in as administrator" and provide that to a client.
[src:security/json-web-token] The client could then use that token to prove that it is logged in as admin.
[src:security/json-web-token] The tokens can be signed by one party's private key (usually the server's) so that any party can subsequently verify whether the token is legitimate.
[src:security/json-web-token] If the other party, by some suitable and trustworthy means, is in possession of the corresponding public key, they too are able to verify the token's legitimacy.
[src:security/json-web-token] The tokens are designed to be compact, URL-safe, and usable, especially in a web-browser single-sign-on (SSO) context.
[src:security/json-web-token] JWT claims can typically be used to pass identity of authenticated users between an identity provider and a service provider, or any other type of claims as required by business processes.
[src:security/json-web-token] JWT relies on other JSON-based standards: JSON Web Signature and JSON Web Encryption.
[src:security/json-web-token] Identifies which algorithm is used to generate the signature.
[src:security/json-web-token] indicates that this token is signed using HMAC-SHA256.
[src:security/json-web-token] JWA (JSON Web Algorithms) RFC 7518 introduces many more for both authentication and encryption.
[src:security/json-web-token] Custom claims are usually also included, depending on the purpose of the token.
[src:security/json-web-token] and concatenating the two together with a period separator.
[src:security/json-web-token] That string is then run through the cryptographic algorithm specified in the header.
[src:security/json-web-token] This example uses HMAC-SHA256 with a shared secret (public key algorithms are also defined).
[src:security/json-web-token] , but uses different non-alphanumeric characters and omits padding.
[src:security/json-web-token] This resulting token can be easily passed into HTML and HTTP.
[src:security/json-web-token] In authentication, when a user successfully logs in, a JSON Web Token (JWT) is often returned.
[src:security/json-web-token] This token should be sent to the client using a secure mechanism like an HTTP-only cookie.
[src:security/json-web-token] Storing the JWT locally in browser storage mechanisms like local or session storage is discouraged.
[src:security/json-web-token] This is because JavaScript running on the client-side (including browser extensions) can access these storage mechanisms, exposing the JWT and compromising security.
[src:security/json-web-token] By using this method, the JWT is never exposed to client-side JavaScript; this is the best approach to make use of your JWT while maintaining security best practices.
[src:security/json-web-token] When the client wants to access a protected route or resource, the user agent should send the JWT, typically in the `Authorization` HTTP header using the `Bearer` schema.
[src:security/json-web-token] This is a stateless authentication mechanism as the user state is never saved in server memory.
[src:security/json-web-token] The server's protected routes will check for a valid JWT in the Authorization header, and if it is present, the user will be allowed to access protected resources.
[src:security/json-web-token] As JWTs are self-contained, all the necessary information is there, reducing the need to query the database multiple times.
[src:security/json-web-token] List of currently registered claim names can be obtained from IANA JSON Web Token Claims Registry.
[src:security/json-web-token] JSON web tokens may contain session state.
[src:security/json-web-token] But if project requirements allow session invalidation before JWT expiration, services can no longer trust token assertions by the token alone.
[src:security/json-web-token] To validate that the session stored in the token is not revoked, token assertions must be checked against a data store.
[src:security/json-web-token] This renders the tokens no longer stateless, undermining the primary advantage of JWTs.
[src:security/json-web-token] Security consultant Tim McLean reported vulnerabilities in some JWT libraries that used the `alg` field to incorrectly validate tokens, most commonly by accepting a `alg=none` token.
[src:security/json-web-token] While these vulnerabilities were patched, McLean suggested deprecating the `alg` field altogether to prevent similar implementation confusion.
[src:security/json-web-token] Still, new `alg=none` vulnerabilities are still being found in the wild, with four CVEs filed in the 2018-2021 period having this cause.
[src:security/json-web-token] Several JWT libraries were found to be vulnerable to an invalid Elliptic-curve attack in 2017.
[src:security/json-web-token] Some have argued that JSON web tokens are difficult to use securely due to the many different encryption algorithms and options available in the standard, and that alternate standards should be used instead for both web frontends and backends.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet is focused on providing developers with concentrated guidance on building application logging mechanisms, especially related to security logging.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Many systems enable network device, operating system, web server, mail server and database server logging, but often custom application event logging is missing, disabled or poorly configured.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] It provides much greater insight than infrastructure logging alone.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Web application (e.g. web site or web service) logging is much more than having web server logs enabled (e.g. using Extended Log File Format).
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should be consistent within the application, consistent across an organization's application portfolio and use industry standards where relevant, so the logged event data can be consumed, correlated, analyzed and managed by a wide variety of systems.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logging should always be included for security events.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Application logs are invaluable data for both security and operational use cases.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Process monitoring, audit, and transaction logs/trails etc. are usually collected for different purposes than security event logging, and this often means they should be kept separate.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The types of events and details collected will tend to be different.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] For example a PCIDSS audit log will contain a chronological record of activities to provide an independently verifiable trail that permits reconstruction, review and examination to determine the original sequence of attributable transactions.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] It is important not to log too much, or too little.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Use knowledge of the intended purposes to guide what, when and how much.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The remainder of this cheat sheet primarily discusses security event logging.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The application itself has access to a wide range of information events that should be used to generate log entries.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Thus, the primary event data source is the application code itself.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The application has the most information about the user (e.g. identity, roles, permissions) and the context of the event (target, action, outcomes), and often this data is not available to either infrastructure devices, or even closely-related applications.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The degree of confidence in the event information has to be considered when including event data from systems in a different trust zone.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Data may be missing, modified, forged, replayed and could be malicious – it must always be treated as untrusted data.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider how the source can be verified, and how integrity and non-repudiation can be enforced.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications commonly write event log data to the file system or a database (SQL or NoSQL).
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Applications installed on desktops and on mobile devices may use local storage and local databases, as well as sending data to remote storage.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Your selected framework may limit the available choices.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] All types of applications may send event data to remote systems (instead of or as well as more local storage).
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] This could be a centralized log collection and management system (e.g.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] SIEM or SEM) or another application elsewhere.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether the application can simply send its event stream, unbuffered, to stdout, for management by the execution environment.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider separate files/tables for extended event information such as error stack traces or a record of HTTP request and response headers and bodies.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The level and content of security monitoring, alerting, and reporting needs to be set during the requirements and design stage of projects, and should be proportionate to the information security risks.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] This can then be used to define what should be logged.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] There is no one size fits all solution, and a blind checklist approach can lead to unnecessary "alarm fog" that means real problems go undetected.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Each log entry needs to include sufficient information for the intended subsequent monitoring and analysis.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] It could be full content data, but is more likely to be an extract or just summary properties.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The application logs must record "when, where, who and what" for each event.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] For more information on these, see the "other" related articles listed at the end, especially the comprehensive article by Anton Chuvakin and Gunnar Peterson.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Never log data unless it is legally sanctioned.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, intercepting some communications, monitoring employees, and collecting some data without consent may all be illegal.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Never exclude any events from "known" users such as other internal systems, "trusted" third parties, search engine robots, uptime/process and other remote monitoring systems, pen testers, auditors.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] However, you may want to include a classification flag for each of these in the recorded data.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider using personal data de-identification techniques such as deletion, scrambling or pseudonymization of direct and indirect identifiers where the individual's identity is not required, or the risk is considered too great.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] In some systems, sanitization can be undertaken post log collection, and prior to log display.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] It may be desirable to be able to alter the level of logging (type of events based on severity or threat level, amount of detail recorded).
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] If your development framework supports suitable logging mechanisms, use or build upon that.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Otherwise, implement an application-wide log handler which can be called from other modules/components.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Document the interface referencing the organisation-specific event classification and description syntax requirements.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] If possible create this log handler as a standard module that can be thoroughly tested, deployed in multiple applications, and added to a list of approved and recommended modules.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Where possible, record data in a standard format, or at least ensure it can be exported/broadcast using an industry-standard format.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] In some cases, events may be relayed or collected together in intermediate points.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] In the latter some data may be aggregated or summarized before forwarding on to a central repository and analysis system.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] As an example, the diagram below shows a service that provides business functionality to customers.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] We recommend creating a centralized system for collecting logs.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] There may be many such services, but all of them must securely collect logs in a centralized system.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] For example, all external requests from users go through the API management service, see application in MIDDLEWARE 2 segment.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] As you can see in the image above, at the network level, the processes of saving and downloading logs require opening different network accesses (ports), arrows are highlighted in different colors.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Also, saving and downloading are performed by different applications.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Enable processes to detect whether logging has stopped, and to identify tampering or unauthorized access and deletion (see protection below).
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] The logging mechanisms and collected event data must be protected from mis-use such as tampering in transit, and unauthorized access, modification and deletion once stored.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Logs may contain personal and other sensitive information, or the data may contain information regarding the application's code and logic.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] In addition, the collected information in the logs may itself have business value (to competitors, gossip-mongers, journalists and activists) such as allowing the estimate of revenues, or providing performance information about employees.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] This data may be held on end devices, at intermediate points, in centralized repositories and in archives and backups.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Consider whether parts of the data may need to be excluded, masked, sanitized, hashed, or encrypted during examination or extraction.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] See `NIST SP 800-92` Guide to Computer Security Log Management for more guidance.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Log data, temporary debug logs, and backups/copies/extractions, must not be destroyed before the duration of the required data retention period, and must not be kept beyond this time.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Legal, regulatory and contractual obligations may impact on these periods.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Because of their usefulness as a defense, logs may be a target of attacks.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] See also OWASP Log Injection and CWE-117.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] A confidentiality attack enables an unauthorized party to access sensitive information stored in logs.
[src:security/logging-cheat-sheet] Which information should be modifiable by whom?
[src:security/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:security/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:security/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:security/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:security/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:security/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:security/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:security/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:security/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:security/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:security/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:security/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:security/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:security/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:security/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:security/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:security/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:security/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:security/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:security/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:security/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:security/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:security/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:security/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:security/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:security/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:security/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:security/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:security/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:security/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:security/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:security/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:security/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:security/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:security/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:security/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:security/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:security/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:security/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:security/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:security/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:security/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:security/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:security/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:security/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:security/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:security/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:security/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:security/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:security/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:security/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:security/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:security/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:security/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:security/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:security/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:security/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:security/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:security/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:security/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:security/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:security/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:security/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:security/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:security/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:security/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:security/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:security/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:security/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:security/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet advises you on the proper methods for storing passwords for authentication.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When passwords are stored, they must be protected from an attacker even if the application or database is compromised.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Fortunately, a majority of modern languages and frameworks provide built-in functionality to help store passwords safely.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Passwords should never be stored in plain text.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Instead, they must be protected using strong, slow hashing algorithms such as Argon2id, bcrypt, or PBKDF2.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] A unique salt must be added to each password to prevent attackers from using precomputed lookup tables like rainbow tables.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Fast hashing algorithms such as SHA‑256 are not suitable for password storage because they allow attackers to perform large numbers of guesses quickly.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Using slow, memory‑hard algorithms makes brute‑force attacks significantly more difficult, expensive, and time‑consuming.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Because **hashing is a one-way function** (i.e., it is impossible to "decrypt" a hash and obtain the original plaintext value), it is the most appropriate approach for password validation.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Even if an attacker obtains the hashed password, they cannot use it to log in as the victim.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Since **encryption is a two-way function**, attackers can retrieve the original plaintext from the encrypted data.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It can be used to store data such as a user's address since this data is displayed in plaintext on the user's profile.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Hashing their address would result in a garbled mess.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The only time encryption should be used in passwords is in edge cases where it is necessary to obtain the original plaintext password.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This might be necessary if the application needs to use the password to authenticate with another system that does not support a modern way to programmatically grant access, such as OpenID Connect (OIDC).
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Wherever possible, an alternative architecture should be used to avoid the need to store passwords in an encrypted form.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For further guidance on encryption, see the Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] While the number of permutations can be enormous, with high speed hardware (such as GPUs) and cloud services with many servers for rent, the cost to an attacker is relatively small to do successful password cracking, especially when best practices for hashing are not followed.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] A salt is a unique, randomly generated string that is added to each password as part of the hashing process.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] As the salt is unique for every user, an attacker has to crack hashes one at a time using the respective salt rather than calculating a hash once and comparing it against every stored hash.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This makes cracking large numbers of hashes significantly harder, as the time required grows in direct proportion to the number of hashes.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Salting also protects against an attacker's pre-computing hashes using rainbow tables or database-based lookups.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Finally, salting means that it is impossible to determine whether two users have the same password without cracking the hashes, as the different salts will result in different hashes even if the passwords are the same.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] At the algorithm and specification level, modern password hashing functions such as Argon2id, bcrypt, and PBKDF2 require the caller to provide a salt.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, most widely used implementations and libraries automatically generate and manage salts internally, so application developers typically do not need to handle salt generation manually when using these libraries correctly.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Peppering is a class of strategies that can be used in addition to salting to provide an additional layer of protection.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It prevents an attacker from being able to crack any of the hashes if they only have access to the database, for example, if they have exploited a SQL injection vulnerability or obtained a backup of the database.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this strategy, a pepper is added to a password before being hashed by a password hashing algorithm.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The computed hash is then stored in the database.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this case the pepper should be a random value generated securely.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] See the Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet for more information on securely generating random values.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this strategy, a password is hashed as usual using a password hashing algorithm.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The resulting password hash is then hashed again using an HMAC (e.g., HMAC-SHA256, HMAC-SHA512, depending on the desired output length) before storing the resulting hash in the database.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] In this case the pepper is acting as the HMAC key and should be generated as per requirements of the HMAC algorithm.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor is the number of iterations of the hashing algorithm that are performed for each password (usually, it's actually `2^work` iterations).
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor is typically stored in the hash output.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] It makes calculating the hash more computationally expensive, which in turn reduces the speed and/or increases the cost for which an attacker can attempt to crack the password hash.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When you choose a work factor, strike a balance between security and performance.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Though higher work factors make hashes more difficult for an attacker to crack, they will slow down the process of verifying a login attempt.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If the work factor is too high, the performance of the application may be degraded, which could be used by an attacker to carry out a denial of service attack by exhausting the server's CPU with a large number of login attempts.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] There is no golden rule for the ideal work factor - it will depend on the performance of the server and the number of users on the application.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Determining the optimal work factor will require experimentation on the specific server(s) used by the application.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] As a general rule, calculating a hash should take less than one second.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] One key advantage of having a work factor is that it can be increased over time as hardware becomes more powerful and cheaper.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The most common approach to upgrading the work factor is to wait until the user next authenticates, then re-hash their password with the new work factor.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The different hashes will have different work factors and hashes may never be upgraded if the user doesn't log back into the application.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Depending on the application, it may be appropriate to remove the older password hashes and require users to reset their passwords next time they need to login in order to avoid storing older and less secure hashes.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Some modern hashing algorithms have been specifically designed to securely store passwords.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This means that they should be slow (unlike algorithms such as MD5 and SHA-1, which were designed to be fast), and you can change how slow they are by changing the work factor.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] You do not need to hide which password hashing algorithm is used by an application.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If you utilize a modern password hashing algorithm with proper configuration parameters, it should be safe to state in public which password hashing algorithms are in use and be listed here.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When selecting a password hashing algorithm, developers should prefer modern algorithms that are designed to resist both GPU-based and memory-based attacks.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Where available, newer algorithms should be chosen for new applications, while older algorithms may still be acceptable for legacy systems with appropriate configuration.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Three hashing algorithms that should be considered.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Argon2 was the winner of the 2015 Password Hashing Competition.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Out of the three Argon2 versions, use the Argon2id variant since it provides a balanced approach to resisting both side-channel and GPU-based attacks.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Rather than a simple work factor like other algorithms, Argon2id has three different parameters that can be configured: the base minimum of the minimum memory size (m), the minimum number of iterations (t), and the degree of parallelism (p).
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These parameters control how computationally expensive it is to compute a password hash.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Increasing memory usage, iteration count, or parallelism makes password cracking attempts significantly slower and more costly for attackers, while still remaining practical for legitimate authentication requests when tuned appropriately.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings provide an equal level of defense, and the only difference is a trade off between CPU and RAM usage.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] scrypt is a password-based key derivation function created by Colin Percival.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] While Argon2id should be the best choice for password hashing, scrypt should be used when the former is not available.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Like Argon2id, scrypt has three parameters that can be configured: the minimum memory cost parameter (N), the blocksize (r), and the degree of parallelism (p).
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings provide a similar minimal level of defense, with the main trade-off between parallelism and RAM usage.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The bcrypt password hashing function **should only** be used for password storage in legacy systems where Argon2 and scrypt are not available.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor should be as large as verification server performance will allow, with a minimum of 10.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] bcrypt has a maximum length input length of 72 bytes for most implementations, so you should enforce a maximum password length of 72 bytes (or less if the bcrypt implementation in use has smaller limits).
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] An alternative approach is to pre-hash the user-supplied password with a fast algorithm such as SHA-2, HMAC, or BLAKE3 and then to hash the resulting hash value with bcrypt (i.e., `bcrypt(H($password)), $salt, $cost)`)..
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] This can be **dangerous** because of null bytes in the hash output value and because of password shucking.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The original bcrypt expects a null terminated password string, this means that the hash value will only be used to the first null byte in the hash value.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Password shucking uses the fact, that it is easy to check if `bcrypt(base64(H($password))), $salt, $cost) == bcrypt(base64($leaked_hash), $salt, $cost)`.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] If the inner hash function `H` is used with the same password somewhere else and known to an attacker cracking the password can be reduced to breaking the hash function `H`.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] `bcrypt(base64(sha512($password))), $salt, $cost)`) is a **dangerous practice** and is as secure as just using pure SHA-512.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Password shucking only works if a leaked hash is known to the attacker, either through a breach database or rainbow tables.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] To mitigate password shucking a pepper can be used.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] To summarize if bcrypt has to be used and the password should to be pre-hashed you should do `bcrypt(base64(hmac-sha384(data:$password, key:$pepper)), $salt, $cost)` and store the pepper not in the database.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Since PBKDF2 is recommended by NIST and has FIPS-140 validated implementations, it should be the preferred algorithm when these are required.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The PBKDF2 algorithm requires that you select an internal hashing algorithm such as an HMAC or a variety of other hashing algorithms.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] HMAC-SHA-256 is widely supported and is recommended by NIST.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] The work factor for PBKDF2 is implemented through an iteration count, which should be set differently based on the internal hashing algorithm used.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These configuration settings are equivalent in the defense they provide.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When PBKDF2 is used with an HMAC, and the password is longer than the hash function's block size (64 bytes for SHA-256), the password will be automatically pre-hashed.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, the password "This is a password longer than 512 bits which is the block size of SHA-256" is converted to the hash value (in hex): `fa91498c139805af73f7ba275cca071e78d78675027000c99a9925e2ec92eedd`.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Good implementations of PBKDF2 perform pre-hashing before the expensive iterated hashing phase.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, some implementations perform the conversion on each iteration, which can make hashing long passwords significantly more expensive than hashing short passwords.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When users supply very long passwords, a potential denial of service vulnerability could occur, such as the one published in Django during 2013.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Manual pre-hashing can reduce this risk but requires adding a salt to the pre-hash step.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Older applications that use less secure hashing algorithms, such as MD5 or SHA-1, can be upgraded to modern password hashing algorithms as described above.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] When the users enter their password (usually by authenticating on the application), that input should be re-hashed using the new algorithm.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Defenders should expire the users' current password and require them to enter a new one, so that any older (less secure) hashes of their password are no longer useful to an attacker.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] However, this means that old (less secure) password hashes will be stored in the database until the user logs in.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] You can take one of two approaches to avoid this dilemma.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Upgrade Method One: Expire and delete the password hashes of users who have been inactive for an extended period and require them to reset their passwords to login again.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Although secure, this approach is not particularly user-friendly.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Expiring the passwords of many users may cause issues for support staff or may be interpreted by users as an indication of a breach.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Upgrade Method Two: Use the existing password hashes as inputs for a more secure algorithm.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] For example, if the application originally stored passwords as `md5($password)`, this could be easily upgraded to `bcrypt(md5($password))`.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Layering the hashes avoids the need to know the original password; however, it can make the hashes easier to crack.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] These hashes should be replaced with direct hashes of the users' passwords next time the user logs in.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Remember that once your password hashing method is selected, it will have to be upgraded in the future, so ensure that upgrading your hashing algorithm is as easy as possible.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] During the transition period, allow for a mix of old and new hashing algorithms.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Using a mix of hashing algorithms is easier if the password hashing algorithm and work factor are stored with the password using a standard format, for example, the modular PHC string format.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Your hashing library must be able to accept a wide range of characters and should be compatible with all Unicode codepoints, so users can use the full range of characters available on modern devices - especially mobile keyboards.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] They should be able to select passwords from various languages and include pictograms.
[src:security/password-storage-cheat-sheet] Prior to hashing the entropy of the user's entry should not be reduced, and password hashing libraries need to be able to use input that may contain a NULL byte.
[src:security/pbkdf2] In cryptography, **PBKDF1** and **PBKDF2** (**Password-Based Key Derivation Function 1** and **2**) are key derivation functions with a sliding computational cost, used to reduce vulnerability to brute-force attacks.
[src:security/pbkdf2] PBKDF2 is part of RSA Laboratories' Public-Key Cryptography Standards (PKCS) series, specifically PKCS #5 v2.0, also published as Internet Engineering Task Force's RFC 2898.
[src:security/pbkdf2] It supersedes PBKDF1, which could only produce derived keys up to 160 bits long.
[src:security/pbkdf2] RFC 8018 (PKCS #5 v2.1), published in 2017, recommends PBKDF2 for password hashing.
[src:security/pbkdf2] PBKDF2 applies a pseudorandom function, such as hash-based message authentication code (HMAC), to the input password or passphrase along with a salt value and repeats the process many times to produce a *derived key*, which can then be used as a cryptographic key in subsequent operations.
[src:security/pbkdf2] The added computational work makes password cracking much more difficult, and is known as key stretching.
[src:security/pbkdf2] While the recommended minimum number of iterations was 1,000 when the standard was written in the year 2000, the parameter is intended to be increased over time as CPU speeds increase.
[src:security/pbkdf2] A Kerberos standard in 2005 recommended 4,096 iterations; Apple reportedly used 2,000 for iOS 3, and 10,000 for iOS 4; while LastPass in 2011 used 5,000 iterations for JavaScript clients and 100,000 iterations for server-side hashing.
[src:security/pbkdf2] Having a salt added to the password reduces the ability to use precomputed hashes (rainbow tables) for attacks, and means that multiple passwords have to be tested individually, not all at once.
[src:security/pbkdf2] The public key cryptography standard recommends a salt length of at least 64 bits.
[src:security/pbkdf2] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology recommends a salt length of at least 128 bits.
[src:security/pbkdf2] The function F is the xor (^) of *c* iterations of chained PRFs.
[src:security/pbkdf2] The first iteration of PRF uses *Password* as the PRF key and *Salt* concatenated with *i* encoded as a big-endian 32-bit integer as the input.
[src:security/pbkdf2] PBKDF1 had a simpler process: the initial *U* (called *T* in this version) is created by PRF(*Password* + *Salt*), and the following ones are simply PRF(*U*previous).
[src:security/pbkdf2] The key is extracted as the first *dkLen* bits of the final hash, which is why there is a size limit.
[src:security/pbkdf2] PBKDF2 has an interesting property when using HMAC as its pseudo-random function.
[src:security/pbkdf2] It is possible to trivially construct any number of different password pairs with collisions within each pair.
[src:security/pbkdf2] If a supplied password is longer than the block size of the underlying HMAC hash function, the password is first pre-hashed into a digest, and that digest is instead used as the password.
[src:security/pbkdf2] These derived key collisions do not represent a security vulnerability – as one still must know the original password in order to generate the *hash* of the password.
[src:security/pbkdf2] In 2013, the Password Hashing Competition (PHC) was held to develop a more resistant approach.
[src:security/pbkdf2] On 20 July 2015 Argon2 was selected as the final PHC winner, with special recognition given to four other password hashing schemes: Catena, Lyra2, yescrypt and Makwa.
[src:security/pbkdf2] Another alternative is Balloon hashing, which is recommended in NIST password guidelines.
[src:security/pbkdf2] To limit a brute-force attack, it is possible to make each password attempt require an online interaction, without harming the confidentiality of the password.
[src:security/pbkdf2] This can be done using an oblivious pseudorandom function to perform password hardening.
[src:security/pbkdf2] This can be done as alternative to, or as an additional step in, a PBKDF.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] REST (or **RE**presentational **S**tate **T**ransfer) is an architectural style first described in Roy Fielding's Ph.D. dissertation on Architectural Styles and the Design of Network-based Software Architectures.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It evolved as Fielding wrote the HTTP/1.1 and URI specs and has been proven to be well-suited for developing distributed hypermedia applications.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] While REST is more widely applicable, it is most commonly used within the context of communicating with services via HTTP.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The key abstraction of information in REST is a resource.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A REST API resource is identified by a URI, usually a HTTP URL.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] REST components use connectors to perform actions on a resource by using a representation to capture the current or intended state of the resource and transferring that representation.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The primary connector types are client and server, secondary connectors include cache, resolver and tunnel.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Stateful APIs do not adhere to the REST architectural style.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] State in the REST acronym refers to the state of the resource which the API accesses, not the state of a session within which the API is called.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] While there may be good reasons for building a stateful API, it is important to realize that managing sessions is complex and difficult to do securely.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] In order to implement flows with REST APIs, resources are typically created, read, updated and deleted.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] For example, an ecommerce site may offer methods to create an empty shopping cart, to add items to the cart and to check out the cart.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Each of these REST calls is stateless and the endpoint should check whether the caller is authorized to perform the requested operation.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another key feature of REST applications is the use of standard HTTP verbs and error codes in the pursuit or removing unnecessary variation among different services.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another key feature of REST applications is the use of HATEOAS or Hypermedia As The Engine of Application State.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This provides REST applications a self-documenting nature making it easier for developers to interact with a REST service without prior knowledge.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Secure REST services must only provide HTTPS endpoints.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This protects authentication credentials in transit, for example passwords, API keys or JSON Web Tokens.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It also allows clients to authenticate the service and guarantees integrity of the transmitted data.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See the Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet for additional information.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Consider the use of mutually authenticated client-side certificates to provide additional protection for highly privileged web services.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Non-public REST services must perform access control at each API endpoint.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Web services in monolithic applications implement this by means of user authentication, authorization logic and session management.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This has several drawbacks for modern architectures which compose multiple microservices following the RESTful style.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] There seems to be a convergence towards using JSON Web Tokens (JWT) as the format for security tokens.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] JWTs are JSON data structures containing a set of claims that can be used for access control decisions.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A cryptographic signature or message authentication code (MAC) can be used to protect the integrity of the JWT.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] If MACs are used for integrity protection, every service that is able to validate JWTs can also create new JWTs using the same key.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] This means that all services using the same key have to mutually trust each other.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Another consequence of this is that a compromise of any service also compromises all other services sharing the same key.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The relying party or token consumer validates a JWT by verifying its integrity and claims contained.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Some claims have been standardized and should be present in JWT used for access controls.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] As JWTs contain details of the authenticated entity (user etc.) a disconnect can occur between the JWT and the current state of the users session, for example, if the session is terminated earlier than the expiration time due to an explicit logout or an idle timeout.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] When an explicit session termination event occurs, a unique, server-issued identifier (the `jti` claim, optionally combined with `aud`) should be submitted to a denylist on the API which will invalidate that JWT for any requests until the expiration of the token.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See the JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet for further details.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Public REST services without access control run the risk of being farmed leading to excessive bills for bandwidth or compute cycles.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] API keys can be used to mitigate this risk.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] They are also often used by organisation to monetize APIs; instead of blocking high-frequency calls, clients are given access in accordance to a purchased access plan.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] API keys can reduce the impact of denial-of-service attacks.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, when they are issued to third-party clients, they are relatively easy to compromise.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] In Java EE in particular, this can be difficult to implement properly.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] See Bypassing Web Authentication and Authorization with HTTP Verb Tampering for an explanation of this common misconfiguration.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Modern REST APIs often implement business workflows through a sequence of endpoints (for example, create → validate → approve → finalize).
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] If the backend does not explicitly validate workflow state transitions, attackers may invoke endpoints out of sequence to bypass intended controls.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Because each endpoint may be individually authenticated and authorized, traditional access control checks often fail to detect these issues.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] A REST request or response body should match the intended content type in the header.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Otherwise this could cause misinterpretation at the consumer/producer side and lead to code injection/execution.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] It is common for REST services to allow multiple response types (e.g.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] `application/xml` or `application/json`, and the client specifies the preferred order of response types by the Accept header in the request.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] JavaScript) in their responses must be especially careful to defend against header injection attack.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] There are a number of security related headers that can be returned in the HTTP responses to instruct browsers to act in specific ways.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, some of these headers are intended to be used with HTML responses, and as such may provide little or no security benefits on an API that does not return HTML.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Note that if the API is only consumed by non-browser clients (e.g. mobile apps, server-to-server calls, command-line tools), most of these headers will have no effect since they are directives for browsers.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] The headers below are only intended to provide additional security when responses are rendered as HTML.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] As such, if the API will **never** return HTML in responses, then these headers may not be necessary.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] However, if there is any uncertainty about the function of the headers, or the types of information that the API returns (or may return in future), then it is recommended to include them as part of a defence-in-depth approach.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS) is a W3C standard to flexibly specify what cross-domain requests are permitted.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] By delivering appropriate CORS Headers your REST API signals to the browser which domains, AKA origins, are allowed to make JavaScript calls to the REST service.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] RESTful web services should be careful to prevent leaking credentials.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Passwords, security tokens, and API keys should not appear in the URL, as this can be captured in web server logs, which makes them intrinsically valuable.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] `https://example.com/controller/123/action?apiKey=a53f435643de32` because the apiKey is in the URL.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] When designing REST API, don't just use `200` for success or `404` for error.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Always use the semantically appropriate status code for the response.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Here is a non-exhaustive selection of security related REST API **status codes**.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Use it to ensure you return the correct code.
[src:security/rest-security-cheat-sheet] Additional information about HTTP return code usage in REST API can be found here and here.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets are being used everywhere nowadays, especially with the popularity of the DevOps movement.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Application Programming Interface (API) keys, database credentials, Identity and Access Management (IAM) permissions, Secure Shell (SSH) keys, certificates, etc.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Many organizations have them hardcoded within the source code in plaintext, littered throughout configuration files and configuration management tools.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There is a growing need for organizations to centralize the storage, provisioning, auditing, rotation and management of secrets to control access to secrets and prevent them from leaking and compromising the organization.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Often, services share the same secrets, which makes identifying the source of compromise or leak challenging.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This cheat sheet offers best practices and guidelines to help properly implement secrets management.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The following sections address the main concepts relating to secrets management.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Such a service could receive a considerable volume of requests within a large organization.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets used by your DevOps teams for your applications might be consumed differently than secrets stored by your marketeers or your SRE team.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You often find poorly maintained secrets where the needs of secret consumers or producers mismatch.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, you must standardize and centralize the secrets management solution with care.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Standardizing and centralizing can mean that you use multiple secret management solutions.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance: your cloud-native development teams choose to use the solution provided by the cloud provider, while your private cloud uses a third-party solution, and everybody has an account for a selected password manager.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By making sure that the teams standardize the interaction with these different solutions, they remain maintainable and usable in the event of an incident.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Even when a company centralizes its secrets management to just one solution, you will often have to secure the primary secret of that secrets management solution in a secondary secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance, you can use a cloud provider's facilities to store secrets, but that cloud provider's root/management credentials need to be stored somewhere else.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Standardization should include Secrets life cycle management, Authentication, Authorization, and Accounting of the secrets management solution, and life cycle management.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note that it should be immediately apparent to an organization what a secret is used for and where to find it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The more Secrets management solutions you use, the more documentation you need.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When users can read and/or update the secret in a secret management system, it means that the secret can now leak through that user and the system they used to touch the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, engineers should not have access to all secrets in the secrets management system, and the Least Privilege principle should be applied.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret management system needs to provide the ability to configure fine-grained access controls on each object and component to accomplish the Least Privilege principle.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Manual maintenance not only increases the risk of leakage; it also introduces the risk of human errors while maintaining the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, it is better to limit or remove the human interaction with the actual secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Rotating certain keys, such as encryption keys, might trigger full or partial data re-encryption.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In a Kubernetes environment, a common pattern is to use a sidecar container that is responsible for retrieving secrets from a secrets manager and making them available to the main application container.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This decouples the application from the specifics of the secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Cloud-native secret managers often provide built-in support for automated rotation using serverless functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure Functions).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These examples demonstrate how you can create architectures that not only manage secrets securely but also automate the rotation process, significantly reducing the risk of compromised credentials.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] An additional level of security can be achieved by minimizing the time window where a secret is in memory and limiting the access to its memory space.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on your application's particular circumstances, this can be difficult to implement in a manner that ensures memory security.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Because of this potential implementation complexity, you are first encouraged to develop a threat model in order to clearly surface your implicit assumptions about both your application's deployment environment as well as understand the capabilities of your adversaries.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Also, it should be kept in mind while developing an appropriate threat model, that if an attacker already has access to the memory of the process handling the secret, by that time a security breach may have already occurred.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, it should be recognized that with the advent of attacks like Rowhammer, or Meltdown and Spectre, it is important to understand that the operating system alone is not sufficient to protect your process memory from these types of attacks.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This becomes especially important when your application is deployed to the cloud.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The only foolproof approach to protecting memory against these and similar attacks is to fully physically isolate your process memory from all other untrusted processes.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Despite the implementation difficulties, in highly sensitive environments, protecting secrets in memory can be a valuable additional layer of security.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, in scenarios where an advanced attacker can cause a system to crash and gain access to a memory dump, they may be able to extract secrets from it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, carefully safeguarding secrets in memory is recommended for untrusted environments or situations where tight security is of utmost importance.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, in lower-level languages like C/C++, it is relatively easy to protect secrets in memory.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, it may be worthwhile to implement this practice even if the risk of an attacker gaining access to the memory is low.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] On the other hand, for programming languages that rely on garbage collection, securing secrets in memory generally is much more difficult.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Remember, the goal is to minimize the time window where the secret is in plaintext in memory as much as possible.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For more detailed information, see Testing Memory for Sensitive Data from the OWASP MAS project.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Auditing is an essential part of secrets management due to the nature of the application.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You must implement auditing securely to be resilient against attempts to tamper with or delete the audit logs.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is essential that all auditing has correct timestamps.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, the secret management solution should have proper time sync protocols set up at its supporting infrastructure.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should monitor the stack on which the solution runs for possible clock-skew and manual time adjustments.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] New secrets must be securely generated and cryptographically robust enough for their purpose.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets must have the minimum privileges assigned to them to enable their required use/role.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should transmit credentials securely, such that ideally, you don't send the password along with the username when requesting user accounts.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead, you should send the password via a secure channel (e.g., mutually authenticated connection) or a side-channel such as push notification, SMS, email.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Refer to the Multi-Factor Authentication Cheat Sheet to learn about the pros and cons of each channel.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Applications may not benefit from having multiple communication channels, so you must provision credentials securely.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Open CRE project on secrets lookup for more technical recommendations on secret creation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should regularly rotate secrets so that any stolen credentials will only work for a short time.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Regular rotation will also reduce the tendency for users to fall back to bad habits such as reusing credentials.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Depending on a secret's function and what it protects, the lifetime could be from minutes (think end-to-end encrypted chats with perfect forward secrecy) to years (consider hardware secrets).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] User credentials are excluded from regular rotation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These should only be rotated if there is suspicion or evidence that they have been compromised, according to NIST recommendations.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When secrets are no longer required or potentially compromised, you must securely revoke them to restrict access.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With (TLS) certificates, this also involves certificate revocation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should create secrets to expire after a defined time where possible.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This expiration can either be active expiration by the secret consuming system, or an expiration date set at the secrets management system forcing supporting processes to be triggered, resulting in a secret rotation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should apply policies through the secrets management solution to ensure credentials are only made available for a limited time appropriate for the type of credentials.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Applications should verify that the secret is still active before trusting it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In this day and age, there is no excuse given the ubiquitous adoption of TLS.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Furthermore, you can effectively use secrets management solutions to provision TLS certificates.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consider the possibility that a secrets management service becomes unavailable for various reasons, such as scheduled downtime for maintenance.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It could be impossible to retrieve the credentials required to restore the service if you did not previously acquire them.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, choose maintenance windows carefully based on earlier metrics and audit logs.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, the backup and restore procedures of the system should be regularly tested and audited for their security.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A few requirements regarding backup & restore.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Lastly, you should implement emergency ("break-glass") processes to restore the service if the system becomes unavailable for reasons other than regular maintenance.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, emergency break-glass credentials should be regularly backed up securely in a secondary secrets management system and tested routinely to verify they work.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consistently enforce policies defining the minimum complexity requirements of passwords and approved encryption algorithms at an organization-wide level.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Using a centralized secrets management solution can help companies implement these policies.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, having an organization-wide secrets management policy can help enforce applying the best practices defined in this cheat sheet.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note: if you don't store metadata about the secret nor prepare to move, you will increase the probability of vendor lock-in.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] While not a direct replacement for all types of secrets (e.g., API keys, database credentials), passwordless authentication mechanisms like **OpenID Connect (OIDC)** can significantly reduce the attack surface by moving away from user-managed passwords.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead of passwords, applications rely on trusted identity providers (IdPs) to authenticate users and receive secure tokens.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Adopting passwordless authentication shifts the security focus from protecting static passwords to protecting dynamic tokens (e.g., ID tokens, access tokens, refresh tokens).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] These tokens are bearer tokens, meaning anyone who possesses one can use them.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For more detailed guidance on securing OAuth 2.0 and OpenID Connect implementations, refer to the OAuth2 Cheat Sheet.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Building, testing and deploying changes generally requires access to many systems.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Continuous Integration (CI) and Continuous Deployment (CD) tools typically store secrets to provide configuration to the application or during deployment.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, they interact heavily with the secrets management system.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Various best practices can help smooth out secret management in CI/CD; we will deal with some of them in this section.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling consumes (high-privilege) credentials regularly.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure that the pipeline cannot be easily hacked or misused by employees.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another alternative here is using the CI/CD pipeline to leverage the Encryption as a Service from the secrets management systems to do the encryption of a secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The CI/CD tooling can then commit the encrypted secret to git, which can be fetched by the consuming service on deployment and decrypted again.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Note: not all secrets must be in the CI/CD pipeline to get to the actual deployment.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead, make sure that the deployed services take care of part of their secrets management at their own lifecycle (e.g., deployment, runtime and destruction).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When secrets are part of your CI/CD tooling, it means that these secrets are exposed to your CI/CD jobs.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling can comprise, e.g., GitHub secrets, GitLab repository secrets, ENV Vars/Var Groups in Microsoft Azure DevOps, Kubernetes Secrets, etc.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Naturally, you can store secrets in a designated secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For example, you can use a solution offered by your (cloud) infrastructure provider, such as AWS Secrets Manager, Google Secrets Manager, or Azure Key Vault.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can find more information about these in section 4 of this cheat sheet.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another option is a dedicated secrets management system, such as Hashicorp Vault, Keeper, Conjur.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Here are a few do's and don'ts for the CI/CD interaction with these systems.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Secrets do not necessarily need to be brought to a consumer of the secret by a CI/CD pipeline.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is even better when the consumer of the secret retrieves the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In that case, the CI/CD pipeline still needs to instruct the orchestrating system (e.g., Kubernetes) that it needs to schedule a specific service with a given service account with which the consumer can then retrieve the required secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The CI/CD tooling then still has credentials for the orchestrating platform but no longer has access to the secrets themselves.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The do's and don'ts regarding these credentials types are similar to those described in section 3.2.2.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CI/CD tooling should have designated service accounts, which can only operate in the scope of the required secrets or orchestration of the consumers of a secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, a CI/CD pipeline run should be easily attributable to the one who has defined the job or triggered it to detect who has tried to exfiltrate secrets or manipulate them.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When you use certificate-based auth, the caller of the pipeline identity should be part of the certificate.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you use a token to authenticate towards the mentioned systems, make sure you set the principal requesting these actions (e.g., the user or the job creator).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Verify on a periodic basis whether this is (still) the case for your system so that you can do logging, attribution, and security alerting on suspicious actions effectively.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Attackers can use CI/CD tooling to extract secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] They could, for example, use administrative interfaces or job creation that exfiltrates the secret using encryption or double Base64 encoding.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Therefore, you should log every action in a CI/CD tool.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should define security alerting rules at every non-standard manipulation of the pipeline tool and its administrative interface to monitor secret usage.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Logs should be queryable for at least 90 days and stored for a more extended period in cold storage.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It might take security teams time to understand how attackers can exfiltrate or manipulate a secret using CI/CD tooling.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can leverage CI/CD tooling to rotate secrets or instruct other components to do the rotation of the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance, the CI/CD tool can request a secrets management system or another application to rotate the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, the CI/CD tool or another component could set up a dynamic secret: a secret required for a consumer to use for as long as it lives.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret is invalidated when the consumer no longer lives.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This procedure reduces possible leakage of a secret and allows for easy detection of misuse.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If an attacker uses a secret from anywhere other than the consumer's IP, you can easily detect it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can use pipeline tooling to generate secrets and either offer them directly to the service deployed by the tooling or provide the secret to a secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Alternatively, the secret can be stored encrypted in git so that the secret and its metadata is as close to the developer's daily place of work as possible.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A git-stored secret does require that developers cannot decrypt the secrets themselves and that every consumer of a secret has its encrypted variant of the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For instance: the secret should then be different per DTAP environment and be encrypted with another key.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For each environment, only the designated consumer in that environment should be able to decrypt the specific secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A secret does not leak cross-environment and can still be easily stored next to the code.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Consumers of a secret could now decrypt the secret using a sidecar, as described in section 5.2.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Instead of retrieving the secrets, the consumer would leverage the sidecar to decrypt the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When a pipeline creates a secret by itself, ensure that the scripts or binaries involved adhere to best practices for secret generation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Best practices include secure randomness, proper length of secret creation, etc. and that the secret is created based on well-defined metadata stored somewhere in git or somewhere else.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is best to use a designated secret management solution in any environment.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Most cloud providers have at least one service that offers secret management.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Of course, it's also possible to run a different secret management solution (e.g., HashiCorp Vault or Conjur) on compute resources within the cloud.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] We'll consider cloud provider service offerings in this section.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Sometimes it's possible to automatically rotate your secret, either via a service provided by your cloud provider or a (custom-built) function.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Generally, you should prefer the cloud provider's solution since the barrier of entry and risk of misconfiguration are lower.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you use a custom solution, ensure the function's role to do its rotation can only be assumed by said function.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For AWS, the recommended solution is AWS Secrets Manager.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Permissions are granted at the secret level.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Check out the Secrets Manager best practices.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With AWS Nitro Enclaves, you can create isolated compute environments to further protect and securely process highly sensitive data such as secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Enclaves are hardened, and restrict operator access, providing a trusted execution environment.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] A key feature is cryptographic attestation, which allows you to verify the enclave's identity and ensure only authorized code is running before provisioning secrets to it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This makes it a strong choice for scenarios requiring high assurance in secret handling.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For secrets being used in highly confidential applications, it may be needed to have more control over the encryption and storage of these keys.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] AWS offers CloudHSM, which lets you bring your own key (BYOK) for AWS services.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Thus, you will have more control over keys' creation, lifecycle, and durability.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] CloudHSM allows automatic scaling and backup of your data.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The cloud service provider, Amazon, will not have any access to the key material stored in **AWS CloudHSM**.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For GCP, the recommended service is Secret Manager.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Check out the Secret Manager best practices.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] GCP Confidential Computing is a technology that encrypts data in-use, while it is being processed.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This is achieved through services like **Confidential VMs** and **Confidential GKE Nodes**, which leverage AMD Secure Encrypted Virtualization (SEV).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This ensures that even Google personnel cannot view the contents of the memory of your virtual machines, providing a high degree of protection for secrets that must be held in memory.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For Azure, the recommended service is Key Vault.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Contrary to other clouds, permissions are granted at the ***Key Vault*** level.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This means secrets for separate workloads and separate sensitivity levels should be in separated Key Vaults accordingly.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] With Azure Confidential Computing, you can create trusted execution environments.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This technology isolates sensitive data within a protected container, ensuring that it is encrypted both at rest, in transit, and in use.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Services like **Azure Confidential Virtual Machines** and **Confidential Containers on ACI** utilize technologies like Intel SGX and AMD SEV-SNP to create these secure enclaves.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This prevents unauthorized access from cloud administrators, malware, or other tenants, making it a robust solution for secret management.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] For secrets being used in Azure environments and requiring special security considerations, Azure offers Azure Dedicated HSM.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This allows you more control over the secrets stored on it, including enhanced administrative and cryptographic control.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The cloud service provider, Microsoft, will not have any access to the key material stored in Azure Dedicated HSM.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] If you're using multiple cloud providers, you should consider using a cloud-agnostic secret management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This will allow you to use the same secret management solution across all your cloud providers (and possibly also on-premises).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Another advantage is that this avoids vendor lock-in with a specific cloud provider, as the solution can be used on any cloud provider.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There are open-source and commercial solutions available.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This section will describe how a secret is encrypted and how you can manage the keys for that encryption in the cloud.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Server-side encryption of secrets ensures that the cloud provider takes care of the encryption of the secret in storage.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The secret is then safeguarded against compromise while at rest.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Encryption at rest often does not require additional work other than selecting the key to encrypt it with (See section 4.2.2).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] However, when you submit the secret to another service, it will no longer be encrypted.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is decrypted before sharing with the intended service or human user.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side encryption of secrets ensures that the secret remains encrypted until you actively decrypt it.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] This means it is only decrypted when it arrives at the consumer.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You need to have a proper crypto system to cater for this.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Think about mechanisms such as PGP using a safe configuration and other more scalable and relatively easy to use systems.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Client-side encryption can provide an end-to-end encryption of the secret: from producer to consumer.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When you encrypt a secret at rest, the question is: which key do you want to use?
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The less trust you have in the cloud provider, the more you will want to manage yourself.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Often, you can either encrypt a secret with a key managed at the secrets management service or use a key management solution from the cloud provider to encrypt the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The key offered through the key management solution of the cloud provider can be either managed by the cloud provider or by yourself.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Industry standards call the latter "bring your own key" (BYOK).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can either directly import or generate this key at the key management solution or using cloud HSM supported by the cloud provider.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can then either use your key or the customer main key from the provider to encrypt the data key of the secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The data key, in turn, encrypts the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By managing the CMK, you have control over the data key at the secrets management solution.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] While importing your own key material can generally be done with all providers (AWS, Azure, GCP), unless you know what you are doing and your threat model and policy require this, this is not a recommended solution due to its complexity and difficulty of use.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] IAM applies to both on-premises and cloud setups: to effectively manage secrets, you need to set up suitable access policies and roles.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Setting this up goes beyond policies regarding secrets; it should include hardening the full IAM setup, as it could otherwise allow for privilege escalation attacks.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure you never allow open "pass role" privileges or unrestricted IAM creation privileges, as these can use or create credentials that have access to the secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, make sure you tightly control what can impersonate a service account: are your machines' roles accessible by an attacker exploiting your server?
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Can service roles from the data-pipeline tooling access the secrets easily?
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Ensure you include IAM for every cloud component in your threat model (e.g., ask yourself: how can you do elevation of privileges with this component?).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See this blog entry for multiple do's and don'ts with examples.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Leverage the temporality of the IAM principals effectively: e.g., ensure that only specific roles and service accounts that require it can access the secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Monitor these accounts so that you can tell who or what used them to access the secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Next, make sure that you scope access to your secrets: one should not be simply allowed to access all secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In GCP and AWS, you can create fine-grained access policies to ensure that a principal cannot access all secrets at once.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] In Azure, having access to the key vault means having access to all secrets in that key vault.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] It is, thus, essential to have separate key vaults when working on Azure to segregate access.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Cloud services can generally provide a limited amount of API calls over a given period.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You could potentially (D)DoS yourself when you run into these limits.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Most of these limits apply per account, project, or subscription, so spread workloads to limit your blast radius accordingly.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Additionally, some services may support data key caching, preventing load on the key management service API (see, for example, AWS data key caching).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Some services can leverage built-in data key caching.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You can enrich containers with secrets in multiple ways: build time (not recommended) and during orchestration/deployment.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] There are three ways to get secrets to an app inside a Docker container.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] To inject secrets, you could create short-lived sidecar containers that fetch secrets from some remote endpoint and then store them on a shared volume mounted to the original container.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The original container can now use the secrets from the mounted volume.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] The benefit of using this approach is that we don't need to integrate any third-party tool or code to get secrets.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Once the sidecar has fetched the secrets, it terminates.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Examples of this include Vault Agent Sidecar Injector and Conjur Secrets Provider.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] By mounting secrets to a volume shared with the pod, containers within the pod can consume secrets without being aware of the secrets manager.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] You should only expose secrets to communication mechanisms between the container and the deployment representation (e.g., a Kubernetes Pod).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] Never expose secrets through external access mechanisms shared among deployments or orchestrators (e.g., a shared volume).
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] When the orchestrator stores secrets (e.g., Kubernetes Secrets), make sure that the storage backend of the orchestrator is encrypted and you manage the keys well.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p01] See the Kubernetes Security Cheat Sheet for more information.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] In this section, we will discuss implementation.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that it is always best to refer to the official documentation of the secrets management system of choice for the actual implementation as it will be more up to date than any secondary document such as this cheat sheet.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Note that these dynamic secrets often need to be created with the service we need to connect to.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] To create these types of dynamic secrets, we usually require long-term static secrets to create the dynamic secrets themselves.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets should never be retrievable by everyone and everything.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Continually monitor who/what, from which IP, and what methodology accesses the secret.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] For a secrets management solution to be effective, it must be easy for developers to adopt and use.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] If the process is too complex, developers may resort to insecure practices.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] A focus on usability and a smooth onboarding experience is critical.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Secrets Management goes hand in hand with encryption.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] After all, secrets must be stored encrypted somewhere to protect their confidentiality and integrity.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] You can use various encryption types to secure a secret as long as they provide sufficient security, including adequate resistance against quantum computing-based attacks.
[src:security/secrets-management-cheat-sheet-p02] Please note that in all cases, we need to preferably select an algorithm that provides encryption and confidentiality at the same time, such as AES-256 using GCM (Galois Counter Mode), or a mixture of ChaCha20 and Poly1305 according to the best practices in the field.
